{"title_page": "Valerie Jarrett", "text_new": "{{short description|American businesswoman and former government official}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Valerie Jarrett\n|image        = Valerie Jarrett official portrait small.jpg\n|office       = Director of the <br>[[White House Office of Public Engagement and Intergovernmental Affairs|Office of Public Engagement and Intergovernmental Affairs]]\n|president    = [[Barack Obama]]\n|term_start   = January 20, 2009\n|term_end     = January 20, 2017\n|predecessor  = [[Julie E. Cram|Julie Cram]] <br>(Public Liaison Office)\n|successor    = [[George Sifakis]] <br>(Public Liaison Office)\n|office1      = [[Senior Advisor to the President of the United States|Senior Advisor to the President]]\n|president1   = [[Barack Obama]]\n|term_start1  = January 20, 2009\n|term_end1    = January 20, 2017\n|predecessor1 = [[Barry Steven Jackson|Barry Jackson]]\n|successor1   = [[Jared Kushner]]<br>[[Stephen Miller (political operative)|Stephen Miller]]\n|birth_name   = Valerie June Bowman\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1956|11|14}}\n|birth_place  = [[Shiraz]], [[Pahlavi dynasty|Iran]]\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse       = {{Marriage|William Jarrett|1983|1988|end=div}}\n|children     = 1\n|parents      = {{unbulleted list|[[Barbara T. Bowman]]|[[James E. Bowman]]}}\n|education    = [[Stanford University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[University of Michigan]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n}}\n'''Valerie June Jarrett''' (n\u00e9e '''Bowman'''; born November 14, 1956)<ref name=hamilton2014>{{cite web|last1=Hamilton|first1=William|title=Valerie Jarrett: The  woman who stays for dinner|url=https://www.skyhinews.com/news/opinion/valerie-jarrett-the-woman-who-stays-for-dinner/|website=www.skyhinews.com|accessdate=May 29, 2018|language=en|date=August 21, 2014}}</ref> is an American businesswoman and former government official. She served as the [[Senior Advisor to the President of the United States|senior advisor]] to [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[Barack Obama]] and assistant to the president for [[White House Office of Public Engagement and Intergovernmental Affairs|public engagement and intergovernmental affairs]] from 2009 to 2017. Before that, she served as a co-chair of the [[Obama\u2013Biden Transition Project]].<ref name=Terry>{{cite web | accessdate=August 23, 2008 | url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/politics/chi-072708-jarrett,0,1640738.story | author=Terry, Don | title=Insider has Obama's ear: What's she telling him? | work=Chicago Tribune | date=July 27, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080729102408/http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/politics/chi-072708-jarrett,0,1640738.story | archive-date=July 29, 2008 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=CNN_King_20081109>{{cite news|accessdate=\n|url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2008/11/09/source-obama-wants-valerie-jarrett-to-replace-him-in-senate/\n|date=November 9, 2008\n|title= Obama wants Valerie Jarrett to replace him in Senate\n|first=John |last=King |authorlink=John King (journalist) |publisher=CNNPolitics.com}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nJarrett was born in [[Shiraz]], Iran,<ref name=hamilton2014 /> during the [[Pahlavi dynasty]], to American parents [[James E. Bowman]] and [[Barbara T. Bowman]]. Her father, a pathologist and geneticist, ran a hospital for children in Shiraz in 1956 as part of a program where American physicians and agricultural experts sought to help in the health and farming efforts of developing countries. When she was five years old, the family moved to London for a year, later moving to Chicago in 1963.<ref>{{Citation | journal = Time | title = 2-Min Bio: Valerie Jarrett | date = November 11, 2008}}.</ref>\n\nHer parents are both of European and African-American descent. On the television series ''[[Finding Your Roots]]'', DNA testing indicated that Jarrett is of 49% European, 46% African, and 5% Native American descent. Among her European roots, she was found to have French and Scottish ancestry.<ref>Stated on ''[[Finding Your Roots]]'', PBS, October 28, 2014.</ref> One of her maternal great-grandfathers, [[Robert Robinson Taylor]], was the first accredited African-American architect, and the first African-American student enrolled at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]].<ref name=\"encyclopedia\">[[Ellen Weiss (academic)|Ellen Weiss]], [http://www.encyclopediaofalabama.org/face/Article.jsp?id=h-3252 \"Robert Robinson Taylor\"], ''[[Encyclopedia of Alabama]]''</ref> Jarrett's father once told her that her great-grandfather was Jewish.<ref>https://forward.com/schmooze/135922/when-valerie-jarrett-revealed-her-jewish-roots/</ref>\n\nAs a child, Jarrett spoke [[Persian language|Persian]], [[French language|French]], and English.<ref name=NYT_Kantor_20081123>{{cite news| last=Kantor| first=Jodi| authorlink=Jodi Kantor| title=An Old Hometown Mentor, Still at Obama's Side| date=November 23, 2008| work= [[The New York Times]]| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/24/us/politics/24jarrett.html?pagewanted=all}}</ref> In 1966, her mother was one of four child advocates who created the [[Erikson Institute]]. The institute was established to provide collective knowledge in child development for teachers and other professionals working with young children.<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.erikson.edu/default/aboutei/history.aspx | title = History | publisher = The Erikson Institute | access-date = November 9, 2008 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080925191525/http://www.erikson.edu/default/aboutei/history.aspx | archive-date = September 25, 2008 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}.</ref> She graduated from [[Northfield Mount Hermon]] in 1974, and earned a B.A. in psychology from [[Stanford University]] in 1978 and a [[Juris Doctor]] [[(J.D.)]] from the [[University of Michigan Law School]] in 1981.<ref>{{Citation | url = http://news.uchicago.edu/article/2009/01/09/valerie-jarrett-leave-university-chicago-posts-white-house | publisher = University of Chicago | title = Valerie Jarrett to leave University of Chicago posts for White House | date = January 9, 2009 | quote = ... Stanford University in 1978 and a Juris Doctor from the University of Michigan Law School in 1981}}.</ref> On May 21, 2016, Jarrett received the [[honorary degree]] of [[Doctor of Laws]] from [[Colby College]] in [[Waterville, Maine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.colby.edu/commencement/2016/honorary-degree-citations/|title=Honorary Degree Citations|date=May 22, 2016|website=Commencement|language=en-US|access-date=June 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Chicago municipal politics===\nJarrett got her start in Chicago politics in 1987 working for [[Mayor of Chicago|Mayor]] [[Harold Washington]]<ref name=NewsweekFamilyFriend>{{cite web|accessdate=August 23, 2008 | url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/136349 | title=Campaign 2008: The Family Friend: Valerie Jarrett | date=May 19, 2008 | work=[[Newsweek]]}}</ref> as deputy corporation counsel for finance and development.<ref name=UCMed2006>{{cite press release | title=Valerie Jarrett to lead expanded Board of University of Chicago Medical Center | date=June 13, 2006 | publisher=University of Chicago News Office}}</ref>\n\nJarrett continued to work in the mayor's office in the 1990s. She was deputy chief of staff for Mayor [[Richard M. Daley|Richard Daley]], during which time (1991) she hired [[Michelle Obama|Michelle Robinson]], then engaged to [[Barack Obama]], away from a private law firm. Jarrett served as commissioner of the department of planning and development from 1992 through 1995, and she was chairwoman of the [[Chicago Transit Board]] from 1995 to 2005.<ref name=\"UCMed2006\"/>\n\n===Business administration===\nUntil joining the Obama administration, Jarrett was the CEO of the Habitat Company, a real estate development and management company,<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.habitat.com/ | title = The Habitat Company}}.</ref> which she joined in 1995. She was replaced by Mark Segal, an attorney who joined the company in 2002, as CEO. Daniel E. Levin is the chairman of Habitat, which was formed in 1971.<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.chicagorealestatedaily.com/cgi-bin/news.pl?id=32907 | title = Habitat promotes veteran to CEO | first = Alby | last = Gallun | newspaper = Chicago Real Estate Daily (Crain's) | date = February 5, 2009 | accessdate = May 4, 2009}}.</ref> Jarrett was a member of the board of [[Chicago Stock Exchange]] (2000\u20132007, as chairman, 2004\u20132007).\n\nShe was a member of the [[board of trustees]] of the [[University of Chicago Medical Center]] from 1996 to 2009, becoming vice chairwoman in 2002 and chairwoman in 2006.<ref name=UCMed2009>{{cite web\n| accessdate=September 2, 2012\n| url=http://news.uchicago.edu/article/2009/01/09/valerie-jarrett-leave-university-chicago-posts-white-house\n| title=Valerie Jarrett to leave University of Chicago posts for White House \n| year=2009\n| publisher=[[uchicago.edu]]}}</ref> She also served as vice chairwoman of the board of trustees of the [[University of Chicago]] and a trustee of the [[Museum of Science and Industry (Chicago)|Museum of Science and Industry]] in Chicago.<ref name=ForbesProfile2008>{{cite web\n| accessdate=January 11, 2019\n| url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080929050007/https://people.forbes.com/profile/valerie-b-jarrett/56351/\n| title=Valerie Jarrett Profile \n| year=2008\n| publisher=[[Forbes.com]]}}</ref> Jarrett serves on the board of directors of [[USG Corporation]], a Chicago-based building materials corporation.\n\n===Advisor to Barack Obama===\n[[File:Obama and Valerie Jarrett.jpg|thumb|Obama speaks to Jarrett and other staff, August 2009]]\n[[File:Barack Obama chats with Senior Advisor Valerie Jarrett in the Blue Room, White House, 2010.jpg|thumb|Barack Obama and Valerie Jarrett converse in the Blue Room, White House, 2010]]\nJarrett was one of President Obama's longest serving advisors and confidantes and was \"widely tipped for a high-profile position in an Obama administration.\"<ref name=\"Belkin-WSJ\">{{cite web|accessdate= | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB121055336572783989?mod=special_page_campaign2008_topbox | author=Belkin, Douglas | title=For Obama, Advice Straight Up: Valerie Jarrett Is Essential Member of Inner Set | work=[[Wall Street Journal]] | date=May 12, 2008}}</ref><ref name=Bai>{{cite news|accessdate= | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/10/magazine/10politics-t.html?em=&pagewanted=all | first=Matt |last=Bai\n| authorlink=Matt Bai\n| title=Is Obama the End of Black Politics? \n| work=[[New York Times Magazine]] | date=August 10, 2008}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Unlike [[Bert Lance]], who arrived from [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] with President [[Jimmy Carter|[Jimmy] Carter]] and became his budget director, or [[Karen Hughes]], who was President [[George W. Bush|[George W.] Bush]]'s communications manager, Ms. Jarrett isn't a confidante with a particular portfolio. What she does share with these counterparts is a fierce sense of loyalty and a refusal to publicly say anything that may reflect poorly on the candidate\u2014or steal his thunder.<ref name=\"Belkin-WSJ\"/>}}\n\nOn November 14, 2008, President-elect Barack Obama selected Jarrett to serve as a [[Senior Advisor to the President of the United States|senior advisor to the president]] and [[White House Office of Public Engagement and Intergovernmental Affairs|assistant to the president for intergovernmental relations and public liaison]].<ref name=nytimes.com_20081114>{{cite news |publisher=New York Times |date=November 14, 2008 |title=Obama Hires Jarrett for Senior Role |url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/11/14/obama-taps-jarrett-for-senior-role/ |accessdate=January 18, 2010 | first=Jodi | last=Kantor}}</ref>\n\nJarrett was one of three senior advisors to President Obama.<ref name=WhiteHouseProfile_2009>{{cite web\n|accessdate=January 29, 2009 |quote=Valerie B. Jarrett is Senior Advisor and Assistant to the President for Intergovernmental Affairs and Public Liaison\n|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/administration/staff/valerie_jarrett/\n|title=Senior Advisor Valerie Jarrett\n|work=The Administration: White House Staff\n|publisher=WhiteHouse.gov}}</ref> She held the retitled position of assistant to the president for intergovernmental affairs and public engagement,<ref name=WhiteHouseProfile_2009/> managed the [[White House Office of Public Engagement and Intergovernmental Affairs]], and [[Office of Urban Affairs]]; she also chaired the [[White House Council on Women and Girls]] and the White House Office of Olympic, Paralympic, and Youth Sport.<ref name=NYT_Kantor_20081115>{{cite news | last=Kantor | first=Jodi| authorlink=Jodi Kantor | title=Longstanding Obama Advisor Gets Senior Role at the White House | date=November 14, 2008 | work=New York Times\n| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/15/us/politics/15jarrett.html}}</ref> She was part of the [[U.S. State Visit to the UK]] in May 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=US  State Visit, 24 to 26 May 2011 Guest List|url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/LatestNewsandDiary/StateVisitprogrammes/2011/Sta/GuestList.aspx|publisher=Royal Family official website}}</ref>\n\nShe said that the 2011 report ''[[Women in America]]'', which the administration produced for the Council on Women and Girls, would be used to guide policy-making.<ref name=Stolberg>{{cite news|author=[[Stolberg, Sheryl]]|title=White House Issues Report on Women in America|url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/03/01/white-house-issues-report-on-women-in-america/|date=March 1, 2011|work=The New York Times|accessdate=March 5, 2011}}</ref>\n\nJarrett had a staff of approximately three dozen and received full-time [[United States Secret Service|Secret Service]] protection.<ref name=\"otherpower\">{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/02/us/politics/valerie-jarrett-is-the-other-power-in-the-west-wing.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 | title=The Other Power in the West Wing | publisher=NY Times | date=September 1, 2012 | accessdate=May 17, 2013 | author=Becker, Jo}}</ref> Jarrett's role as both a friend of the Obamas and as senior advisor in the White House was controversial:  in his memoirs [[Robert M. Gates]], former [[United States Secretary of Defense|secretary of defense]], discussed his objection to her involvement in foreign security affairs;<ref>Robert M. Gates. ''Duty: memoirs of a secretary at war''. Deckle Edge, 2014</ref> [[David Axelrod (political consultant)|David Axelrod]] reported in his memoirs about [[Rahm Emanuel]]'s attempts to have her selected as Obama's replacement in the senate, due to concerns about the difficulty in working with a family friend in a major policy role.<ref>David Axelrod, ''Believer: my forty years in politics'', Penguin Press, 2015.</ref>\n\n===Additional leadership positions===\nIn addition to being senior advisor to the president, Jarrett held other leadership positions and completed further duties. Among those included chairing the [[White House Council on Women and Girls]] and co-chairing the [[White House Task Force to Protect Students from Sexual Assault]].<ref name=\"Sexualassault\">[http://www.whitehouse.gov/blog/2014/01/22/renewed-call-action-end-rape-and-sexual-assault A renewed call to action to end rape and sexual assault], ''The White House Blog'', Washington, DC: Valerie Jarrett, January 22, 2014, Retrieved January 24, 2014.</ref><ref name=\"Memo\">[http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2014/01/22/memorandum-establishing-white-house-task-force-protect-students-sexual-a Memorandum: Establishing White House Task Force to Protect Students from Sexual Assault], ''WhiteHouse.gov'', Washington, DC: The White House, January 22, 2014, Retrieved June 10, 2014.</ref> In March 2014, she participated as a speaker on [https://www.hsph.harvard.edu/voices/ Voices in Leadership], an original [[Harvard T.H. Chan School of Public Health|Harvard T. H. Chan School of Public Health]] webcast series, in a discussion entitled, \"[https://www.hsph.harvard.edu/voices/events/jarrett/ Leadership in the White House],\" moderated by [[Atul Gawande|Dr. Atul Gawande]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hsph.harvard.edu/voices/events/jarrett/|title=Leadership in the White House|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150914015009/http://www.hsph.harvard.edu/voices/events/jarrett/|archive-date=September 14, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Relationship with the Obamas ===\n[[File:Barack Obama and Valerie Jarrett in the West Wing corridor cropped.jpg|thumb|left|Obama speaks with Jarrett in a West Wing corridor]]\nIn 1991, as deputy chief of staff to Mayor Richard Daley, Jarrett interviewed Michelle Robinson for an opening in the mayor's office, after which she immediately offered Robinson the job.<ref name=\"Vogue_Van Meter_200810\">{{cite news | last= Van Meter | first= Jonathan| title= Barack's Rock | date = October 2008 | work = Vogue | url = http://www.style.com/vogue/feature/2008_Oct_Valerie_Jarrett/}}</ref> Robinson asked for time to think and also asked Jarrett to meet her fianc\u00e9, Barack Obama. The three ended up meeting for dinner. After the dinner, Robinson accepted the job with the mayor's office. It was at this time that Jarrett reportedly took the couple under her wing and \"introduced them to a wealthier and better-connected Chicago than their own.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/24/world/americas/24iht-profile.4.18110914.html|title=Chicago mentor follows Obama to Washington|first=Jodi|last=Kantor|date=November 24, 2008|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> When Jarrett later left her position at the mayor's office to head the Chicago department of planning and development, Michelle Obama went with her.\n\n=== Post-Obama administration ===\nSince leaving the White House, Jarrett has volunteered as a senior advisor to the [[Obama Foundation]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/news/catching-up-with-valerie-jarrett/|title=Catching up with Valerie Jarrett|work=Chicago Sun-Times|access-date=May 30, 2018|language=en}}</ref> In 2017 she was appointed to the board of directors of [[Ariel Investments]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-obama-adviser-valerie-jarrett-ariel-0328-20170327-story.html|title=Former Obama adviser Valerie Jarrett joins Ariel Investments board|last=MarksJarvis|first=Gail|work=chicagotribune.com|access-date=May 30, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> and joined the [[board of directors]] of [[2U (company)|2U, Inc.]], [[Lyft]], and the [[Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/nbcblk/former-obama-advisor-valerie-jarrett-joins-lyft-board-directors-n788606|title=Former Obama adviser joins Lyft Board of Directors|work=NBC News|access-date=May 30, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://fortune.com/2017/12/07/valerie-jarrett-tech-board/|title=Exclusive: Obama Adviser Valerie Jarrett Joins Board of Tech Company 2U|author= Valentina Zarya|publisher=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]|date=December 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/arts-and-entertainment/wp/2017/01/17/obama-names-jarrett-rice-to-kennedy-center-board-of-trustees/?noredirect=on|title=Obama names Jarrett, Rice to Kennedy Center Board of Trustees|author=Peggy McGlone |publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|date=January 17, 2017}}</ref> She is also the co-Chair of the United State of Women, Chair of the Board of When We All Vote, and a Senior Advisor to [[ATTN:]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/on-leadership/wp/2018/03/01/valerie-jarrett-tina-tchen-announce-second-united-state-of-women-summit-in-l-a/|title=Valerie Jarrett, Tina Tchen announce second United State of Women Summit in L.A.|author=Katie Mettler |publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|date=March 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.vox.com/2018/7/19/17590322/michelle-obama-when-we-all-vote|title=Michelle Obama may not want to be your president, but she still wants you to vote|author=Jennie Neufeld|publisher=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|date=July 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/333580-top-obama-official-joins-media-startup-as-senior-adviser|title=Valerie Jarrett joins media startup as senior adviser|author=John Bowden|publisher=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|date=May 16, 2017}}</ref> In January 2018 she became a distinguished senior fellow at the [[University of Chicago Law School]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/chicagoinc/ct-met-valerie-jarrett-1213-chicago-inc-20171212-story.html|title=Valerie Jarrett joins University of Chicago Law School|last=Janssen|first=Kim|work=chicagotribune.com|access-date=May 30, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.uchicago.edu/article/2017/12/11/valerie-jarrett-former-senior-adviser-president-obama-join-university-chicago-law|title=Valerie Jarrett, former senior adviser to President Obama, to join University of Chicago Law School|date=December 11, 2017|work=UChicago News|access-date=May 30, 2018|language=en}}</ref> \n\nIn July 2017 Jarrett signed a deal with [[Viking Press]] for her book titled ''Finding My Voice: My Journey to the West Wing and the Path Forward''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2017/07/11/valerie-jarrett-book-deal-viking-240400|title=Valerie Jarrett signs book deal|work=POLITICO|access-date=May 30, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\nAlong with [[Donna Brazile]], vice chairwoman of the [[Democratic National Committee]], she is one of the real-life political figures to make a [[cameo appearance]] as herself in the [[CBS]] drama ''[[The Good Wife]]''.<ref name=\"USAToday_20140929\">{{cite news|accessdate=February 6, 2015| url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/theoval/2014/09/29/obama-valerie-jarrett-julianna-margulies-the-good-wife/16422345/ | first=David | last=Jackson | title=Valerie Jarrett appears on 'The Good Wife' | publisher=USAToday.com | date=September 29, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn 1983 she married [[William Robert Jarrett]], son of ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' reporter [[Vernon Jarrett]]. She attributes her switch from a private to a public career to the birth of their daughter, and her own desire to do something that would make their daughter proud.<ref name=Vogue>{{Citation | url = http://www.style.com/vogue/feature/2008_Oct_Valerie_Jarrett/ | title = Barack's Rock | first = Jonathan | last = van Meter | journal = [[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] | date = October 2008 | accessdate = December 15, 2008}}.</ref> Her daughter, [[Laura Jarrett]], is an attorney and reporter for [[CNN]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Boyer|first1=Dave|title=Laura Jarrett, Valerie Jarrett daughter, hired by CNN|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2017/jan/20/laura-jarrett-valerie-jarrett-daughter-hired-cnn/|work=The Washington Times|date=January 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/profiles/laura-jarrett|title=CNN Profiles - Laura Jarrett - Reporter - CNN|website=CNN|accessdate=May 30, 2018}}</ref> and daughter-in-law of the Canadian politician [[Bas Balkissoon]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Benzie|first1=Robert|title=Obama attends wedding of Toronto Liberal MPP's son| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2012/06/20/obama_attends_wedding_of_toronto_liberal_mpps_son.html|work=thestar.com|date=June 20, 2012|language=en}}</ref>\n\nTo one reporter's emailed question about her divorce, she replied, \"Married in 1983, separated in 1987, and divorced in 1988. Enough said.\"<ref name=Vogue/> In a ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' profile, she further explained, \"We grew up together. We were friends since childhood. In a sense, he was the boy next door. I married without really appreciating how hard divorce would be.\"<ref name=Vogue/> William Jarrett died on November 19, 1993, at age 40, and at the time of his death was director of obstetrics and gynecology at [[Jackson Park Hospital]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-11-23/news/9311230116_1_vernon-jarrett-opera-and-jazz-medicine|title=Dr. William Jarrett Of Jackson Park Hospital|last=Heise|first=Kenan|date=November 23, 1993|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=January 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n*[https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/administration/senior-leadership/valerie-jarrett Valerie Jarrett] at [[Whitehouse.gov]] (archived at obamawhitehouse.archives.gov)\n*{{C-SPAN|valeriejarrett}}\n*{{Charlie Rose view|6446}}\n*{{NYTtopic|people/j/valerie_jarrett}}\n*{{Worldcat id|np-jarrett,%20valerie}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Julie E. Cram|Julie Cram]]|as=Director of the Office of Public Liaison}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[White House Office of Public Engagement and Intergovernmental Affairs|Director of the Office of Public Engagement and Intergovernmental Affairs]]|years=2009\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[George Sifakis]]|as=Director of the Office of Public Liaison}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Barry Steven Jackson|Barry Jackson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Senior Advisor to the President of the United States|Senior Advisor to the President]]|years=2009\u20132017|alongside=[[Brian Deese]], [[Shailagh Murray]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jared Kushner]]|after2=[[Stephen Miller (political advisor)|Stephen Miller]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Obama Administration personnel}}\n{{WHOPL|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jarrett, Valerie}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:African-American lawyers]]\n[[Category:African-American women in politics]]\n[[Category:African-American women lawyers]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Iran]]\n[[Category:American people of French descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:American women chief executives]]\n[[Category:American women lawyers]]\n[[Category:Illinois Democrats]]\n[[Category:Illinois lawyers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Northfield Mount Hermon School alumni]]\n[[Category:Obama administration personnel]]\n[[Category:People from Shiraz]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Senior Advisors to the President]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago Laboratory Schools alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Women in Illinois politics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American businesswoman and former government official}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Valerie Jarrett\n|image        = Valerie Jarrett official portrait small.jpg\n|office       = [[White House Office of Public Engagement and Intergovernmental Affairs|Director of the Office of Public Engagement and Intergovernmental Affairs]]\n|president    = [[Barack Obama]]\n|term_start   = January 20, 2009\n|term_end     = January 20, 2017\n|predecessor  = [[Julie E. Cram|Julie Cram]] (Public Liaison)\n|successor    = [[George Sifakis]] (Public Liaison)\n|office1      = [[Senior Advisor to the President of the United States|Senior Advisor to the President]]\n|president1   = [[Barack Obama]]\n|term_start1  = January 20, 2009\n|term_end1    = January 20, 2017\n|predecessor1 = [[Barry Steven Jackson|Barry Jackson]]\n|successor1   = [[Jared Kushner]]<br>[[Stephen Miller (political operative)|Stephen Miller]]\n|birth_name   = Valerie June Bowman\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1956|11|14}}\n|birth_place  = [[Shiraz]], [[Pahlavi dynasty|Iran]]\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse       = {{Marriage|William Jarrett|1983|1988|end=div}}\n|children     = 1\n|parents      = {{unbulleted list|[[Barbara T. Bowman]]|[[James E. Bowman]]}}\n|education    = [[Stanford University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[University of Michigan]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n}}\n'''Valerie June Jarrett''' (n\u00e9e '''Bowman'''; born November 14, 1956)<ref name=hamilton2014>{{cite web|last1=Hamilton|first1=William|title=Valerie Jarrett: The  woman who stays for dinner|url=https://www.skyhinews.com/news/opinion/valerie-jarrett-the-woman-who-stays-for-dinner/|website=www.skyhinews.com|accessdate=May 29, 2018|language=en|date=August 21, 2014}}</ref> is an American businesswoman and former government official. She served as the [[Senior Advisor to the President of the United States|senior advisor]] to [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[Barack Obama]] and assistant to the president for [[White House Office of Public Engagement and Intergovernmental Affairs|public engagement and intergovernmental affairs]] from 2009 to 2017. Before that, she served as a co-chair of the [[Obama\u2013Biden Transition Project]].<ref name=Terry>{{cite web | accessdate=August 23, 2008 | url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/politics/chi-072708-jarrett,0,1640738.story | author=Terry, Don | title=Insider has Obama's ear: What's she telling him? | work=Chicago Tribune | date=July 27, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080729102408/http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/politics/chi-072708-jarrett,0,1640738.story | archive-date=July 29, 2008 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=CNN_King_20081109>{{cite news|accessdate=\n|url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2008/11/09/source-obama-wants-valerie-jarrett-to-replace-him-in-senate/\n|date=November 9, 2008\n|title= Obama wants Valerie Jarrett to replace him in Senate\n|first=John |last=King |authorlink=John King (journalist) |publisher=CNNPolitics.com}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nJarrett was born in [[Shiraz]], Iran,<ref name=hamilton2014 /> during the [[Pahlavi dynasty]], to American parents [[James E. Bowman]] and [[Barbara T. Bowman]]. Her father, a pathologist and geneticist, ran a hospital for children in Shiraz in 1956 as part of a program where American physicians and agricultural experts sought to help in the health and farming efforts of developing countries. When she was five years old, the family moved to London for a year, later moving to Chicago in 1963.<ref>{{Citation | journal = Time | title = 2-Min Bio: Valerie Jarrett | date = November 11, 2008}}.</ref>\n\nHer parents are both of European and African-American descent. On the television series ''[[Finding Your Roots]]'', DNA testing indicated that Jarrett is of 49% European, 46% African, and 5% Native American descent. Among her European roots, she was found to have French and Scottish ancestry.<ref>Stated on ''[[Finding Your Roots]]'', PBS, October 28, 2014.</ref> One of her maternal great-grandfathers, [[Robert Robinson Taylor]], was the first accredited African-American architect, and the first African-American student enrolled at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]].<ref name=\"encyclopedia\">[[Ellen Weiss (academic)|Ellen Weiss]], [http://www.encyclopediaofalabama.org/face/Article.jsp?id=h-3252 \"Robert Robinson Taylor\"], ''[[Encyclopedia of Alabama]]''</ref> Jarrett's father once told her that her great-grandfather was Jewish.<ref>https://forward.com/schmooze/135922/when-valerie-jarrett-revealed-her-jewish-roots/</ref>\n\nAs a child, Jarrett spoke [[Persian language|Persian]], [[French language|French]], and English.<ref name=NYT_Kantor_20081123>{{cite news| last=Kantor| first=Jodi| authorlink=Jodi Kantor| title=An Old Hometown Mentor, Still at Obama's Side| date=November 23, 2008| work= [[The New York Times]]| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/24/us/politics/24jarrett.html?pagewanted=all}}</ref> In 1966, her mother was one of four child advocates who created the [[Erikson Institute]]. The institute was established to provide collective knowledge in child development for teachers and other professionals working with young children.<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.erikson.edu/default/aboutei/history.aspx | title = History | publisher = The Erikson Institute | access-date = November 9, 2008 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080925191525/http://www.erikson.edu/default/aboutei/history.aspx | archive-date = September 25, 2008 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}.</ref> She graduated from [[Northfield Mount Hermon]] in 1974, and earned a B.A. in psychology from [[Stanford University]] in 1978 and a [[Juris Doctor]] [[(J.D.)]] from the [[University of Michigan Law School]] in 1981.<ref>{{Citation | url = http://news.uchicago.edu/article/2009/01/09/valerie-jarrett-leave-university-chicago-posts-white-house | publisher = University of Chicago | title = Valerie Jarrett to leave University of Chicago posts for White House | date = January 9, 2009 | quote = ... Stanford University in 1978 and a Juris Doctor from the University of Michigan Law School in 1981}}.</ref> On May 21, 2016, Jarrett received the [[honorary degree]] of [[Doctor of Laws]] from [[Colby College]] in [[Waterville, Maine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.colby.edu/commencement/2016/honorary-degree-citations/|title=Honorary Degree Citations|date=May 22, 2016|website=Commencement|language=en-US|access-date=June 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Chicago municipal politics===\nJarrett got her start in Chicago politics in 1987 working for [[Mayor of Chicago|Mayor]] [[Harold Washington]]<ref name=NewsweekFamilyFriend>{{cite web|accessdate=August 23, 2008 | url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/136349 | title=Campaign 2008: The Family Friend: Valerie Jarrett | date=May 19, 2008 | work=[[Newsweek]]}}</ref> as deputy corporation counsel for finance and development.<ref name=UCMed2006>{{cite press release | title=Valerie Jarrett to lead expanded Board of University of Chicago Medical Center | date=June 13, 2006 | publisher=University of Chicago News Office}}</ref>\n\nJarrett continued to work in the mayor's office in the 1990s. She was deputy chief of staff for Mayor [[Richard M. Daley|Richard Daley]], during which time (1991) she hired [[Michelle Obama|Michelle Robinson]], then engaged to [[Barack Obama]], away from a private law firm. Jarrett served as commissioner of the department of planning and development from 1992 through 1995, and she was chairwoman of the [[Chicago Transit Board]] from 1995 to 2005.<ref name=\"UCMed2006\"/>\n\n===Business administration===\nUntil joining the Obama administration, Jarrett was the CEO of the Habitat Company, a real estate development and management company,<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.habitat.com/ | title = The Habitat Company}}.</ref> which she joined in 1995. She was replaced by Mark Segal, an attorney who joined the company in 2002, as CEO. Daniel E. Levin is the chairman of Habitat, which was formed in 1971.<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.chicagorealestatedaily.com/cgi-bin/news.pl?id=32907 | title = Habitat promotes veteran to CEO | first = Alby | last = Gallun | newspaper = Chicago Real Estate Daily (Crain's) | date = February 5, 2009 | accessdate = May 4, 2009}}.</ref> Jarrett was a member of the board of [[Chicago Stock Exchange]] (2000\u20132007, as chairman, 2004\u20132007).\n\nShe was a member of the [[board of trustees]] of the [[University of Chicago Medical Center]] from 1996 to 2009, becoming vice chairwoman in 2002 and chairwoman in 2006.<ref name=UCMed2009>{{cite web\n| accessdate=September 2, 2012\n| url=http://news.uchicago.edu/article/2009/01/09/valerie-jarrett-leave-university-chicago-posts-white-house\n| title=Valerie Jarrett to leave University of Chicago posts for White House \n| year=2009\n| publisher=[[uchicago.edu]]}}</ref> She also served as vice chairwoman of the board of trustees of the [[University of Chicago]] and a trustee of the [[Museum of Science and Industry (Chicago)|Museum of Science and Industry]] in Chicago.<ref name=ForbesProfile2008>{{cite web\n| accessdate=January 11, 2019\n| url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080929050007/https://people.forbes.com/profile/valerie-b-jarrett/56351/\n| title=Valerie Jarrett Profile \n| year=2008\n| publisher=[[Forbes.com]]}}</ref> Jarrett serves on the board of directors of [[USG Corporation]], a Chicago-based building materials corporation.\n\n===Advisor to Barack Obama===\n[[File:Obama and Valerie Jarrett.jpg|thumb|Obama speaks to Jarrett and other staff, August 2009]]\n[[File:Barack Obama chats with Senior Advisor Valerie Jarrett in the Blue Room, White House, 2010.jpg|thumb|Barack Obama and Valerie Jarrett converse in the Blue Room, White House, 2010]]\nJarrett was one of President Obama's longest serving advisors and confidantes and was \"widely tipped for a high-profile position in an Obama administration.\"<ref name=\"Belkin-WSJ\">{{cite web|accessdate= | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB121055336572783989?mod=special_page_campaign2008_topbox | author=Belkin, Douglas | title=For Obama, Advice Straight Up: Valerie Jarrett Is Essential Member of Inner Set | work=[[Wall Street Journal]] | date=May 12, 2008}}</ref><ref name=Bai>{{cite news|accessdate= | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/10/magazine/10politics-t.html?em=&pagewanted=all | first=Matt |last=Bai\n| authorlink=Matt Bai\n| title=Is Obama the End of Black Politics? \n| work=[[New York Times Magazine]] | date=August 10, 2008}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Unlike [[Bert Lance]], who arrived from [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] with President [[Jimmy Carter|[Jimmy] Carter]] and became his budget director, or [[Karen Hughes]], who was President [[George W. Bush|[George W.] Bush]]'s communications manager, Ms. Jarrett isn't a confidante with a particular portfolio. What she does share with these counterparts is a fierce sense of loyalty and a refusal to publicly say anything that may reflect poorly on the candidate\u2014or steal his thunder.<ref name=\"Belkin-WSJ\"/>}}\n\nOn November 14, 2008, President-elect Barack Obama selected Jarrett to serve as a [[Senior Advisor to the President of the United States|senior advisor to the president]] and [[White House Office of Public Engagement and Intergovernmental Affairs|assistant to the president for intergovernmental relations and public liaison]].<ref name=nytimes.com_20081114>{{cite news |publisher=New York Times |date=November 14, 2008 |title=Obama Hires Jarrett for Senior Role |url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/11/14/obama-taps-jarrett-for-senior-role/ |accessdate=January 18, 2010 | first=Jodi | last=Kantor}}</ref>\n\nJarrett was one of three senior advisors to President Obama.<ref name=WhiteHouseProfile_2009>{{cite web\n|accessdate=January 29, 2009 |quote=Valerie B. Jarrett is Senior Advisor and Assistant to the President for Intergovernmental Affairs and Public Liaison\n|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/administration/staff/valerie_jarrett/\n|title=Senior Advisor Valerie Jarrett\n|work=The Administration: White House Staff\n|publisher=WhiteHouse.gov}}</ref> She held the retitled position of assistant to the president for intergovernmental affairs and public engagement,<ref name=WhiteHouseProfile_2009/> managed the [[White House Office of Public Engagement and Intergovernmental Affairs]], and [[Office of Urban Affairs]]; she also chaired the [[White House Council on Women and Girls]] and the White House Office of Olympic, Paralympic, and Youth Sport.<ref name=NYT_Kantor_20081115>{{cite news | last=Kantor | first=Jodi| authorlink=Jodi Kantor | title=Longstanding Obama Advisor Gets Senior Role at the White House | date=November 14, 2008 | work=New York Times\n| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/15/us/politics/15jarrett.html}}</ref> She was part of the [[U.S. State Visit to the UK]] in May 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=US  State Visit, 24 to 26 May 2011 Guest List|url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/LatestNewsandDiary/StateVisitprogrammes/2011/Sta/GuestList.aspx|publisher=Royal Family official website}}</ref>\n\nShe said that the 2011 report ''[[Women in America]]'', which the administration produced for the Council on Women and Girls, would be used to guide policy-making.<ref name=Stolberg>{{cite news|author=[[Stolberg, Sheryl]]|title=White House Issues Report on Women in America|url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/03/01/white-house-issues-report-on-women-in-america/|date=March 1, 2011|work=The New York Times|accessdate=March 5, 2011}}</ref>\n\nJarrett had a staff of approximately three dozen and received full-time [[United States Secret Service|Secret Service]] protection.<ref name=\"otherpower\">{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/02/us/politics/valerie-jarrett-is-the-other-power-in-the-west-wing.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 | title=The Other Power in the West Wing | publisher=NY Times | date=September 1, 2012 | accessdate=May 17, 2013 | author=Becker, Jo}}</ref> Jarrett's role as both a friend of the Obamas and as senior advisor in the White House was controversial:  in his memoirs [[Robert M. Gates]], former [[United States Secretary of Defense|secretary of defense]], discussed his objection to her involvement in foreign security affairs;<ref>Robert M. Gates. ''Duty: memoirs of a secretary at war''. Deckle Edge, 2014</ref> [[David Axelrod (political consultant)|David Axelrod]] reported in his memoirs about [[Rahm Emanuel]]'s attempts to have her selected as Obama's replacement in the senate, due to concerns about the difficulty in working with a family friend in a major policy role.<ref>David Axelrod, ''Believer: my forty years in politics'', Penguin Press, 2015.</ref>\n\n===Additional leadership positions===\nIn addition to being senior advisor to the president, Jarrett held other leadership positions and completed further duties. Among those included chairing the [[White House Council on Women and Girls]] and co-chairing the [[White House Task Force to Protect Students from Sexual Assault]].<ref name=\"Sexualassault\">[http://www.whitehouse.gov/blog/2014/01/22/renewed-call-action-end-rape-and-sexual-assault A renewed call to action to end rape and sexual assault], ''The White House Blog'', Washington, DC: Valerie Jarrett, January 22, 2014, Retrieved January 24, 2014.</ref><ref name=\"Memo\">[http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2014/01/22/memorandum-establishing-white-house-task-force-protect-students-sexual-a Memorandum: Establishing White House Task Force to Protect Students from Sexual Assault], ''WhiteHouse.gov'', Washington, DC: The White House, January 22, 2014, Retrieved June 10, 2014.</ref> In March 2014, she participated as a speaker on [https://www.hsph.harvard.edu/voices/ Voices in Leadership], an original [[Harvard T.H. Chan School of Public Health|Harvard T. H. Chan School of Public Health]] webcast series, in a discussion entitled, \"[https://www.hsph.harvard.edu/voices/events/jarrett/ Leadership in the White House],\" moderated by [[Atul Gawande|Dr. Atul Gawande]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hsph.harvard.edu/voices/events/jarrett/|title=Leadership in the White House|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150914015009/http://www.hsph.harvard.edu/voices/events/jarrett/|archive-date=September 14, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Relationship with the Obamas ===\n[[File:Barack Obama and Valerie Jarrett in the West Wing corridor cropped.jpg|thumb|left|Obama speaks with Jarrett in a West Wing corridor]]\nIn 1991, as deputy chief of staff to Mayor Richard Daley, Jarrett interviewed Michelle Robinson for an opening in the mayor's office, after which she immediately offered Robinson the job.<ref name=\"Vogue_Van Meter_200810\">{{cite news | last= Van Meter | first= Jonathan| title= Barack's Rock | date = October 2008 | work = Vogue | url = http://www.style.com/vogue/feature/2008_Oct_Valerie_Jarrett/}}</ref> Robinson asked for time to think and also asked Jarrett to meet her fianc\u00e9, Barack Obama. The three ended up meeting for dinner. After the dinner, Robinson accepted the job with the mayor's office. It was at this time that Jarrett reportedly took the couple under her wing and \"introduced them to a wealthier and better-connected Chicago than their own.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/24/world/americas/24iht-profile.4.18110914.html|title=Chicago mentor follows Obama to Washington|first=Jodi|last=Kantor|date=November 24, 2008|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> When Jarrett later left her position at the mayor's office to head the Chicago department of planning and development, Michelle Obama went with her.\n\n=== Post-Obama administration ===\nSince leaving the White House, Jarrett has volunteered as a senior advisor to the [[Obama Foundation]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/news/catching-up-with-valerie-jarrett/|title=Catching up with Valerie Jarrett|work=Chicago Sun-Times|access-date=May 30, 2018|language=en}}</ref> In 2017 she was appointed to the board of directors of [[Ariel Investments]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-obama-adviser-valerie-jarrett-ariel-0328-20170327-story.html|title=Former Obama adviser Valerie Jarrett joins Ariel Investments board|last=MarksJarvis|first=Gail|work=chicagotribune.com|access-date=May 30, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> and joined the [[board of directors]] of [[2U (company)|2U, Inc.]], [[Lyft]], and the [[Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/nbcblk/former-obama-advisor-valerie-jarrett-joins-lyft-board-directors-n788606|title=Former Obama adviser joins Lyft Board of Directors|work=NBC News|access-date=May 30, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://fortune.com/2017/12/07/valerie-jarrett-tech-board/|title=Exclusive: Obama Adviser Valerie Jarrett Joins Board of Tech Company 2U|author= Valentina Zarya|publisher=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]|date=December 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/arts-and-entertainment/wp/2017/01/17/obama-names-jarrett-rice-to-kennedy-center-board-of-trustees/?noredirect=on|title=Obama names Jarrett, Rice to Kennedy Center Board of Trustees|author=Peggy McGlone |publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|date=January 17, 2017}}</ref> She is also the co-Chair of the United State of Women, Chair of the Board of When We All Vote, and a Senior Advisor to [[ATTN:]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/on-leadership/wp/2018/03/01/valerie-jarrett-tina-tchen-announce-second-united-state-of-women-summit-in-l-a/|title=Valerie Jarrett, Tina Tchen announce second United State of Women Summit in L.A.|author=Katie Mettler |publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|date=March 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.vox.com/2018/7/19/17590322/michelle-obama-when-we-all-vote|title=Michelle Obama may not want to be your president, but she still wants you to vote|author=Jennie Neufeld|publisher=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|date=July 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/333580-top-obama-official-joins-media-startup-as-senior-adviser|title=Valerie Jarrett joins media startup as senior adviser|author=John Bowden|publisher=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|date=May 16, 2017}}</ref> In January 2018 she became a distinguished senior fellow at the [[University of Chicago Law School]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/chicagoinc/ct-met-valerie-jarrett-1213-chicago-inc-20171212-story.html|title=Valerie Jarrett joins University of Chicago Law School|last=Janssen|first=Kim|work=chicagotribune.com|access-date=May 30, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.uchicago.edu/article/2017/12/11/valerie-jarrett-former-senior-adviser-president-obama-join-university-chicago-law|title=Valerie Jarrett, former senior adviser to President Obama, to join University of Chicago Law School|date=December 11, 2017|work=UChicago News|access-date=May 30, 2018|language=en}}</ref> \n\nIn July 2017 Jarrett signed a deal with [[Viking Press]] for her book titled ''Finding My Voice: My Journey to the West Wing and the Path Forward''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2017/07/11/valerie-jarrett-book-deal-viking-240400|title=Valerie Jarrett signs book deal|work=POLITICO|access-date=May 30, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\nAlong with [[Donna Brazile]], vice chairwoman of the [[Democratic National Committee]], she is one of the real-life political figures to make a [[cameo appearance]] as herself in the [[CBS]] drama ''[[The Good Wife]]''.<ref name=\"USAToday_20140929\">{{cite news|accessdate=February 6, 2015| url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/theoval/2014/09/29/obama-valerie-jarrett-julianna-margulies-the-good-wife/16422345/ | first=David | last=Jackson | title=Valerie Jarrett appears on 'The Good Wife' | publisher=USAToday.com | date=September 29, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn 1983 she married [[William Robert Jarrett]], son of ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' reporter [[Vernon Jarrett]]. She attributes her switch from a private to a public career to the birth of their daughter, and her own desire to do something that would make their daughter proud.<ref name=Vogue>{{Citation | url = http://www.style.com/vogue/feature/2008_Oct_Valerie_Jarrett/ | title = Barack's Rock | first = Jonathan | last = van Meter | journal = [[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] | date = October 2008 | accessdate = December 15, 2008}}.</ref> Her daughter, [[Laura Jarrett]], is an attorney and reporter for [[CNN]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Boyer|first1=Dave|title=Laura Jarrett, Valerie Jarrett daughter, hired by CNN|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2017/jan/20/laura-jarrett-valerie-jarrett-daughter-hired-cnn/|work=The Washington Times|date=January 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/profiles/laura-jarrett|title=CNN Profiles - Laura Jarrett - Reporter - CNN|website=CNN|accessdate=May 30, 2018}}</ref> and daughter-in-law of the Canadian politician [[Bas Balkissoon]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Benzie|first1=Robert|title=Obama attends wedding of Toronto Liberal MPP's son| url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2012/06/20/obama_attends_wedding_of_toronto_liberal_mpps_son.html|work=thestar.com|date=June 20, 2012|language=en}}</ref>\n\nTo one reporter's emailed question about her divorce, she replied, \"Married in 1983, separated in 1987, and divorced in 1988. Enough said.\"<ref name=Vogue/> In a ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' profile, she further explained, \"We grew up together. We were friends since childhood. In a sense, he was the boy next door. I married without really appreciating how hard divorce would be.\"<ref name=Vogue/> William Jarrett died on November 19, 1993, at age 40, and at the time of his death was director of obstetrics and gynecology at [[Jackson Park Hospital]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-11-23/news/9311230116_1_vernon-jarrett-opera-and-jazz-medicine|title=Dr. William Jarrett Of Jackson Park Hospital|last=Heise|first=Kenan|date=November 23, 1993|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=January 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n*[https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/administration/senior-leadership/valerie-jarrett Valerie Jarrett] at [[Whitehouse.gov]] (archived at obamawhitehouse.archives.gov)\n*{{C-SPAN|valeriejarrett}}\n*{{Charlie Rose view|6446}}\n*{{NYTtopic|people/j/valerie_jarrett}}\n*{{Worldcat id|np-jarrett,%20valerie}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Julie E. Cram|Julie Cram]]|as=Director of the Office of Public Liaison}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[White House Office of Public Engagement and Intergovernmental Affairs|Director of the Office of Public Engagement and Intergovernmental Affairs]]|years=2009\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[George Sifakis]]|as=Director of the Office of Public Liaison}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Barry Steven Jackson|Barry Jackson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Senior Advisor to the President of the United States|Senior Advisor to the President]]|years=2009\u20132017|alongside=[[Brian Deese]], [[Shailagh Murray]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jared Kushner]]|after2=[[Stephen Miller (political advisor)|Stephen Miller]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Obama Administration personnel}}\n{{WHOPL|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jarrett, Valerie}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:African-American lawyers]]\n[[Category:African-American women in politics]]\n[[Category:African-American women lawyers]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Iran]]\n[[Category:American people of French descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:American women chief executives]]\n[[Category:American women lawyers]]\n[[Category:Illinois Democrats]]\n[[Category:Illinois lawyers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Northfield Mount Hermon School alumni]]\n[[Category:Obama administration personnel]]\n[[Category:People from Shiraz]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Senior Advisors to the President]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago Laboratory Schools alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Women in Illinois politics]]\n", "name_user": "Ben76266", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Valerie_Jarrett"}
{"title_page": "2024 Russian presidential election", "text_new": "{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 2024 Russian presidential election\n| country = Russia\n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = yes <!-- PLEASE DO NOT CHANGE THIS UNTIL 2024 -->\n| previous_election = 2018 Russian presidential election\n| previous_year = 2018\n| election_date = 17 March 2024 (1st round)\n| next_election = 2030 Russian presidential election\n| next_year = 2030\n| opinion_polls = Opinion polling for the 2024 Russian presidential election\n| turnout = \n| registered = 110,564,632 (January 2020)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cikrf.ru/izbiratel/quantity/20200101.php|title=\u0421\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043e \u0447\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0437\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0433\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0432 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0445 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438, \u0437\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0430\u043c\u0438 \u0442\u0435\u0440\u0440\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0438 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u0438\u0437\u0431\u0438\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0439, \u0443\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0440\u0435\u0444\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0443\u043c\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u043f\u043e \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u044f\u043d\u0438\u044e \u043d\u0430 1 \u044f\u043d\u0432\u0430\u0440\u044f 2020 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430|publisher=Cikrf.ru |date=2020-01-01 |accessdate=2020-03-01}}</ref>\n| image1 = \n| nominee1 = \n| party1 = \n| home_state1 = \n| popular_vote1 = \n| percentage1 = \n| image2 = \n| nominee2 = \n| party2 = \n| home_state2 = \n| popular_vote2 = \n| percentage2 = \n| image3 = \n| nominee3 = \n| party3 = \n| home_state3 = \n| popular_vote3 = \n| percentage3 = \n| title = President\n| before_election = [[Vladimir Putin]]\n| before_party = Independent politician\n| after_election = \n| after_party = \n}}\nThe '''2024 Russian presidential election''' will take place in March 2024. In accordance with electoral law, the first round will be held on Sunday 17 March 2024.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consultant.ru/document/cons_doc_LAW_40445/c3b8b1b1845f4b4bcb6bfc2a1514d8cc0baccc74/|title=\u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0437\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d \u043e\u0442 10.01.2003 N 19-\u0424\u0417 (\u0440\u0435\u0434. \u043e\u0442 05.12.2017) \"\u041e \u0432\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0445 \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438\" \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0442\u044c\u044f 5. \u041d\u0430\u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0432\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438|website=\u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0442\u041f\u043b\u044e\u0441|accessdate=5 March 2018}}</ref> If in the first round no candidate attains an absolute majority of the votes (more than half), then according to the law a second round will take place exactly three weeks later on 7 April 2024.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consultant.ru/document/cons_doc_LAW_40445/a90a2145a34de6130bfb4367daec059ac75a9614/|title=\u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0437\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d \u043e\u0442 10.01.2003 N 19-\u0424\u0417 (\u0440\u0435\u0434. \u043e\u0442 05.12.2017) \"\u041e \u0432\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0445 \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438\" \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0442\u044c\u044f 77. \u041f\u043e\u0432\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0433\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0445 \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438|website=\u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0442\u041f\u043b\u044e\u0441|accessdate=5 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe term limit established by Article 81 of the Russian Constitution prevents incumbent president [[Vladimir Putin]] from being elected to a new term. The 2024 election will determine the fifth [[President of Russia]]. The winner of the election is scheduled to be [[Russian presidential inauguration|inaugurated]] on 7 May 2024.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consultant.ru/document/cons_doc_LAW_40445/041abf1209079a3f6e2d0e19bca00375bfed931e/|title=\u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0437\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d \u043e\u0442 10.01.2003 N 19-\u0424\u0417 (\u0440\u0435\u0434. \u043e\u0442 05.12.2017) \"\u041e \u0432\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0445 \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438\" \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0442\u044c\u044f 82. \u0412\u0441\u0442\u0443\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0432 \u0434\u043e\u043b\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n===Ineligibility of Vladimir Putin===\n[[File:Vladimir Putin 2019-04-12.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Vladimir Putin]], the incumbent president, whose second term expires on May 7, 2024]]\n\nAccording to point 3 of article 81 of the [[Constitution of Russia]], the same person cannot hold a position of the [[President of the Russian Federation]] more than two terms in a row.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.constitution.ru/en/10003000-05.htm |title=Constitution of Russia. Chapter 4. The President of the Russian Federation. Article 81 |publisher=Constitution.ru |date= |accessdate=2018-03-22}}</ref> This means that [[Vladimir Putin]], who was elected president in [[2012 Russian presidential election|2012]] and re-elected in [[2018 Russian presidential election|2018]], will not be able to participate in the 2024 presidential election, although some experts suggest that Putin may remain in power after 2024.<ref>{{cite web|author=All RFE/RL sites |url=https://www.rferl.org/a/putin-2024-election-raises-curtain-on-clouded-future/29107186.html |title=Putin's 2024 Problem: Election Win Raises Curtain On Clouded Future |publisher=Rferl.org |date=2018-03-18 |accessdate=2018-03-22}}</ref> Putin denied the possibility of his participation in the 2030 election when answering this question of a journalist on 18 March 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ria.ru/20180318/1516701655.html|title=\u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d \u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0438\u043b \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u043e\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441 \u043e \u0432\u043e\u0437\u043c\u043e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u043c \u0443\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0438 \u0432 \u0432\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0445-2030|date=2018-03-18|website=\u0420\u0418\u0410 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438|language=ru|access-date=2018-12-08}}</ref> On 25 May 2018, answering a journalist's question during the [[St. Petersburg International Economic Forum|SPIEF]], Putin said that he was not going to hold the post of president for more than two consecutive terms.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/3641992|title=\u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d \u043d\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043d \u0437\u0430\u043d\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442\u044c \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0431\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0435 \u0434\u0432\u0443\u0445 \u0441\u0440\u043e\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0440\u044f\u0434|publisher=\u041a\u043e\u043c\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0442|date= |accessdate=2018-05-25}}</ref>\n\n====\"2024 problem\"====\nThe \"2024 problem\"<ref>\u0420\u0443\u0431\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0438 \u0436\u0443\u0440\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0430 The New Times [https://newtimes.ru/rubrics/detail/175832/ \u041f\u0440\u043e\u0431\u043b\u0435\u043c\u0430 2024] \u0438 [https://newtimes.ru/rubrics/detail/175832/ \u041f\u0440\u043e\u0431\u043b\u0435\u043c\u0430-2024]</ref> is connected with end of Putin\u2019s presidential powers in 2024.<ref name=\"fedorov\">{{cite book|editor-last=\u0424\u0451\u0434\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432|editor-first=\u0412. \u0412. |others=\u0412. \u0412. \u0424\u0451\u0434\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432, \u042e. \u041c. \u0411\u0430\u0441\u043a\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430, \u041b. \u0413. \u0411\u044b\u0437\u043e\u0432, \u041e. \u041b. \u0427\u0435\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0437\u0443\u0431, \u041c. \u0412. \u041c\u0430\u043c\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432, \u0418. \u0412. \u0413\u0430\u0432\u0440\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0432, \u041c. \u0410. \u0412\u044f\u0434\u0440\u043e|title=\u0412\u042b\u0411\u041e\u0420\u042b \u041d\u0410 \u0424\u041e\u041d\u0415 \u041a\u0420\u042b\u041c\u0410: \u044d\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b 2016\u20142018 \u0433\u0433. \u0438 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0441\u043f\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0432\u044b \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0437\u0438\u0442\u0430|publisher=\u0412\u0426\u0418\u041e\u041c|date=2018|isbn=9785041523244}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Gallup International opinion poll conducted in December 2017, if Putin was not to be on the ballot, 46% would not have known for whom to vote and 19% would have made the ballot paper invalid.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dp.ru/a/2017/12/20/Gallup_bez_uchastija_Vladi|title=Gallup: \u0431\u0435\u0437 \u0443\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438\u044f \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440\u0430 \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0432\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u044b \u0440\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0443\u044e\u0442 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f|website=www.dp.ru}}</ref> Valery Fedorov<ref>Director of [[Russian Public Opinion Research Center]]</ref> said that the Russian population does not think about this problem,<ref>{{cite web |author=\u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 |url=https://www.mk.ru/politics/2019/03/14/konec-epokhi-putina-kak-eto-budet.html |title= \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446 \u044d\u043f\u043e\u0445\u0438 \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430: \u043a\u0430\u043a \u044d\u0442\u043e \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0442 ''\u041f\u0443\u0442\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c \u043f\u043e \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0443\u0449\u0435\u0439 \u0441\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0435 \u0432\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438'' |language=ru |website=|publisher=\u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u00ab\u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u0441\u043e\u043c\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0446\u00bb |date=2019-03-14 |accessdate=2019-08-01}}</ref> while the focus group participants gathered by the [[Levada Center]] identified two main scenarios for its solution: preservation of presidential powers by Vladimir Putin and the appointment of a successor.<ref name=\"volkov\">{{cite web |author=\u0414\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0441 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043a\u043e\u0432 |url=https://www.rbc.ru/newspaper/2019/05/15/5cda6f089a794770fbfb5ec9 |title=\u0427\u0442\u043e \u0434\u0443\u043c\u0430\u044e\u0442 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0438\u0437\u0431\u0438\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0438 \u043e \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0431\u043b\u0435\u043c\u0435-2024 |language=ru |website=rbc.ru |publisher= |date=2019-05-14 |accessdate=2019-08-01}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Ekaterina Schulmann]], a wide elite pact is being sought, the alternative to which is the war of all against all.<ref>{{cite web |author=\u0415\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0428\u0443\u043b\u044c\u043c\u0430\u043d |url=https://www.inliberty.ru/article/shulman/ |title=\u041f\u044f\u0442\u044b\u0439 \u0441\u0440\u043e\u043a |language=ru |website=inliberty.ru |publisher= |date=2018-03-18 |accessdate=2019-08-01}}</ref> According to Oleg Chernozub, the Russian elite is able to find ways to solve this problem,<ref name=\"fedorov\"/> for example, [[Valery Zorkin]] proposed changing the constitution,<ref>{{cite web |author=Anastasia Stognei |url=https://thebell.io/en/russian-political-veteran-suggests-constitutional-tweaks-to-solve-putin-s-2024-problem/ |title=Proposed constitutional changes reveal Kremlin splits over Putin\u2019s \u20182024 problem\u2019 |language=en |website=thebell.io |publisher= |date=2018-10-12 |accessdate=2019-08-01}}</ref> [[Vyacheslav Volodin]] proposed expanding the powers of the parliament.<ref>{{cite web |author=Peter Mironenko |url=https://thebell.io/en/the-russian-elite-is-jostling-to-solve-putin-s-2024-problem/ |title=The Russian elite is jostling to solve Putin\u2019s \u20182024 problem\u2019 |language=en |website=thebell.io |publisher= |date=2019-07-20 |accessdate=2019-08-01}}</ref>\n\nIn general, there are several scenarios for the development of events in the political field of Russia in 2024:<ref name=\"gulf\">{{cite web |author=Andrew Hammond |url=https://gulfnews.com/opinion/op-eds/putin-win-will-put-politics-in-flux-1.2182488 |title=Putin win will put politics in flux |language=en |website=gulfnews.com |publisher= |date=2018-03-04 |accessdate=2019-08-01}}</ref>\n* '''Competitive free elections'''\n*: One of the least likely scenarios is that the next president after Putin will be determined as a result of an open political process.<ref name=\"gulf\"/>\n* '''Assignment of a successor'''<ref name=\"politek4\">{{cite web |author=\u0422\u0430\u0442\u044c\u044f\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043b\u044c\u0447\u0443\u043a, \u0412\u044f\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u041f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043d\u043a\u043e, \u0410\u0440\u043d\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0434 \u0425\u0430\u0447\u0430\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043e\u0432 |url=https://www.novayagazeta.ru/articles/2018/03/30/76001-problema-2024-ili-politekonomiya-chetvertogo-sroka |title=\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0431\u043b\u0435\u043c\u0430-2024, \u0438\u043b\u0438 \u041f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0442\u044d\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0438\u044f \u0447\u0435\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0442\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0441\u0440\u043e\u043a\u0430 |language=ru |website=novayagazeta.ru |publisher= |date=2018-03-30 |accessdate=2019-08-01}}</ref>\n*: One of the most likely scenarios is when [[Vladimir Putin]] will appoint his successor, who will be the main candidate for the 2024 election.<ref name=\"fedorov\" /> Putin himself was successor of [[Boris Yeltsin]], and then [[Dmitry Medvedev]] was Putin's successor for one term.<ref name=\"gulf\" /> Participants of focus groups, among Putin's possible successors, often name [[Dmitry Medvedev]] and [[Sergey Shoygu]], less often [[Sergey Lavrov]], [[Sergey Sobyanin]], or even [[Pavel Grudinin]]; many say that he will be an unknown, \"fresh\" person.<ref name=\"volkov\"/> Political analyst Azhdar Kurtov believes that to ensure the victory of a successor in the elections, there may be recognition of the [[Donetsk People's Republic]] and [[Luhansk People's Republic]] independence.<ref>{{cite web |author=\u0410\u043d\u0434\u0440\u0435\u0439 \u0418\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432 |url=https://svpressa.ru/politic/article/231347/ |title=\u041a\u0440\u0435\u043c\u043b\u044c \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u043d\u0435\u0437\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0441\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u0414\u041d\u0420 \u0438 \u041b\u041d\u0420 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434 \u0432\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0430\u043c\u0438 2024 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 |language=ru |website=svpressa.ru |publisher= |date= |accessdate=2019-08-01}}</ref>\n*: In connection with the alleged transit of power, questions arise - will a successor be able to protect Putin in the same way that Putin protected Yeltsin? Will it be possible to change the president without serious destabilization and internal struggle? And most importantly - can the system built by Putin function without Putin?<ref>{{cite book|first=Tony|last=Wood |title=Russia Without Putin: Money, Power and the Myths of the New Cold War |publisher=Verso Books |date=2018 |pages=174\u2013175/224  |isbn=1788731263 |ref= }}</ref>\n* '''Amendment of the Constitution'''<ref name=\"politek4\" />\n*: Another possible way for Putin to retain power after 2024 called a possible amendment to the  [[Constitution of Russia|Constitution]], removing the limitation of the terms of presidency in order for Putin to run for president in 2024. However, Putin said he was not going to change the Constitution in an interview with [[Megyn Kelly]] in March 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ria.ru/20180310/1516070848.html|title=\u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d \u0437\u0430\u044f\u0432\u0438\u043b, \u0447\u0442\u043e \u043d\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043d \u043c\u0435\u043d\u044f\u0442\u044c \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0446\u0438\u044e|date=2018-03-10|website=\u0420\u0418\u0410 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438|language=ru|access-date=2018-12-08}}</ref>\n*: A scenario in which restrictions that prevent Putin from remaining as president of the Russian Federation will be lifted.<ref name=\"gulf\" /> [[Sergey Alexandrovich Markov|Sergei Markov]] says that Putin\u2019s repeated statements that there will be no abolition of terms of office have led discussion of possible scenarios for 2024 to a standstill.<ref name=\"bloomber\">{{cite web |author=Ilya Arkhipov  & Henry Meyer |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-07-12/putin-seeks-to-lock-in-parliament-control-amid-falling-ratings |title=Putin Seeks to Lock in Parliament Control |language=en |website=bloomberg.com |publisher= |date=2019-07-12 |accessdate=2019-08-01}}</ref> Even a closer union with [[Belarus]] is being discussed.<ref name=\"kreml\">{{cite web |author= |url=http://www.19rus.info/index.php/vlast-i-politika/item/99220-kreml-produmal-neskolko-stsenariev-chtoby-putin-eshche-dolgo-ostavalsya-u-vlasti |title=\u041a\u0440\u0435\u043c\u043b\u044c \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0443\u043c\u0430\u043b \u043d\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043a\u043e \u0441\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0435\u0432, \u0447\u0442\u043e\u0431\u044b \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d \u0435\u0449\u0435 \u0434\u043e\u043b\u0433\u043e \u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0441\u044f \u0443 \u0432\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438 |language=ru |website=19rus.info |publisher= |date= |accessdate=2019-08-01}}</ref>\n* '''Putin retains power, but not as president'''\n*: Putin may take another position in 2024 (as it was from 2008 to 2012) and again run for president in 2030. On 23 March 2018, Presidential Press Secretary [[Dmitry Peskov]] said that Putin is not going to change the Constitution and if there will be any constitutional reform, it will not concern presidential powers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ria.ru/20180323/1517079765.html|title=\u0412 \u041a\u0440\u0435\u043c\u043b\u0435 \u0440\u0430\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043b\u0438, \u043a\u0430\u043a \u043c\u043e\u0436\u0435\u0442 \u043f\u043e\u043c\u0435\u043d\u044f\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0446\u0438\u044f|date=2018-03-23|website=\u0420\u0418\u0410 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438|language=ru|access-date=2018-12-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rg.ru/2018/03/23/peskov-putin-ne-nameren-meniat-pod-sebia-konstituciiu.html|title=\u041f\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0432: \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d \u043d\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043d \u043c\u0435\u043d\u044f\u0442\u044c \u043f\u043e\u0434 \u0441\u0435\u0431\u044f \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0446\u0438\u044e|website=\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0433\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430|language=ru|access-date=2018-12-08}}</ref>\n*: As an option, Putin can choose the posts of the [[List of heads of government of Russia|Prime Minister]]<ref name=\"wegren\">{{cite book|first=Stephen K.|last= Wegren |title=Putin's Russia: Past Imperfect, Future Uncertain |url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=1538114275 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |date=2018 |page=2/360 |isbn=1538114275 |ref= }}</ref> with extended powers<ref name=\"bloomber\"/><ref>{{cite web |author= |url=https://newtimes.ru/articles/detail/182816/ |title=Bloomberg \u0440\u0430\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043b \u043e \u0440\u0435\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0435 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0441\u043e\u0445\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0443 \u0432\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438 |language=ru |website=newtimes.ru |publisher= |date=2019-07-12 |accessdate=2019-08-01}}</ref> or the [[Chairman of the State Duma]].<ref name=\"gulf\" /> This option involves expanding the powers of parliament.<ref name=\"bloomber\" /> Political scientists are also discussing the possibility of transferring powers to the [[Security Council of Russia|Security Council]] or the [[State Council (Russia)|State Council]] of the Russian Federation.<ref name=\"kreml\"/> In January 2020, Putin announced plans to amend the Constitution and expand the powers of the Duma and State Council. This has led to further speculation that he may seek to lead a strengthened State Council after leaving the office of president.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/news/world/putin-outlines-sweeping-powers-for-state-council-in-shakeup|title=Vladimir Putin outlines sweeping powers for state council in Russian government shakeup|publisher=National Post|date=20 January 2020}}</ref> It is also possible that Putin will retain political power without taking a formal position.<ref name=\"wegren\"/>\n\nAccording to political analyst Kirill Rogov, the constitutional design of Russian statehood remains unclear due to the unsuccessful experience of the \u201ctandem\u201d and the lack of institutions of distributed power.<ref>{{cite web |author=\u041a\u0438\u0440\u0438\u043b\u043b \u0420\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0432 |url=https://www.inliberty.ru/article/shulman/ |title=\u041f\u044f\u0442\u044b\u0439 \u0441\u0440\u043e\u043a |language=ru |website=inliberty.ru |publisher= |date=2018-03-18 |accessdate=2019-08-01}}</ref>  In addition to the obvious conflict between [[Putinism|Putin\u2019s political regime]] and the [[Politics of Russia|official state system]], the problem is also the impossibility for Putin to guarantee security for himself and his family if he leaves office completely. However, poor health may encourage him to leave.<ref name=\"dilemma\">{{cite web |author= |url=https://newtimes.ru/articles/detail/177294/ |title=\u0414\u0438\u043b\u0435\u043c\u043c\u0430 \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430: \u0443\u0439\u0442\u0438 \u043d\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0437\u044f \u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f |language=ru |website= |publisher= |date=2019-02-19 |accessdate=2019-08-01}}</ref>\n\n===2020 constitutional reform===\n{{main|2020 amendments to the Constitution of Russia}}\nDuring his [[2020 Presidential Address to the Federal Assembly|annual address to the Federal Assembly]] on 15 January 2020, Putin proposed a constitutional amendments. According to assumptions, this reform will help him maintain influence on the government even after leaving the post of President.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=https://newizv.ru/news/politics/13-02-2020/konstitutsiya-kakie-popravki-odobril-putin?|title=\u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0446\u0438\u044f: \u043a\u0430\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0438 \u043e\u0434\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0438\u043b \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d|language=ru |website= |publisher=\u041d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0435 \u0438\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u044f |date=2020-02-13 |accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author= |url=https://www.mk.ru/social/2020/01/31/polovina-rossiyan-uvidela-v-izmenenii-konstitucii-zhelanie-putina-sokhranit-vlast.html|title=\u041f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044f\u043d \u0443\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0430 \u0432 \u0438\u0437\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u0436\u0435\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0441\u043e\u0445\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0442\u044c \u0432\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044c|language=ru |website= |publisher=\u041c\u041a.RU |date=2020-01-31 |accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\nA number of amendments affect the presidential authority:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sozd.duma.gov.ru/bill/885214-7|title=\u2116885214-7 \u0417\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442 :: \u0421\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043c\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u0435\u0441\u043f\u0435\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0437\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0434\u0435\u044f\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438|website=sozd.duma.gov.ru|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n*Putin proposed to partially weaken the President, and the [[State Duma]] has the right to approve members of the government (with the exception of power Ministers, whose appointment will be under the jurisdiction of the [[Federation Council (Russia)|Federation Council]]). \n*Remove the words \"in a row\" from the article about the maximum number of terms a President (that means that in the future presidents can serve two terms max for life, Putin can't run for President in all subsequent elections, and Dmitry Medvedev will be able to run just once, as previously already served one term as President).\n*Putin proposed to state the role of the [[State Council (Russia)|State Council]] in the Constitution. However, the Constitution will only state that the State Council is formed by the President, as well as the goals of its formation. The main powers of this body are proposed to be documented in an ordinary Federal Law (in March of the same year, Putin said that he was not going to head the state Council after leaving the post of President. In his opinion, such a decision would lead to dual power, which would be disastrous for Russia).<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=https://www.mk.ru/politics/2020/03/06/vladimir-putin-obyasnil-pochemu-ne-vozglavit-gossovet.html|title=\u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d \u043e\u0431\u044a\u044f\u0441\u043d\u0438\u043b, \u043f\u043e\u0447\u0435\u043c\u0443 \u043d\u0435 \u0432\u043e\u0437\u0433\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442 \u0413\u043e\u0441\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442|language=ru |website= |publisher=\u041c\u041a.RU |date=2020-03-06 |accessdate=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n*The amendments will also set stricter requirements for people running for president. Namely, they will have to have lived in Russia for the last 25 years (according to the old norm of 10 years), and the President can not become a person who has or ever had a foreign citizenship or residence permit in another country, while people who previously had citizenship of a country that or part of which became part of Russia will be able to run for president (this means that former Ukrainian citizens who lived in Crimea in 2014 and received Russian citizenship after the annexation of the peninsula will be able to run for president in the future, however, if under the old rule they could run already in these elections. Now they will not be able to do this until 2039).\n*Also, after the amendments, all former presidents will receive the status of senators for life, at the same time, they will have the right to refuse this status.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=https://www.vedomosti.ru/politics/articles/2020/02/11/822786-bivshie-prezidenti-status-senatorov|title=\u0411\u044b\u0432\u0448\u0438\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u044b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0430\u0442 \u043f\u043e\u0436\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0443\u0441 \u0441\u0435\u043d\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0430|language=ru |website= |publisher=\u0412\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 |date=2020-02-11 |accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\nIn order to adopt these amendments, Putin proposed holding a [[2020 Russian constitutional referendum|popular vote]], in accordance with the results of which the amendments will enter into force or be rejected.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=https://tass.com/politics/1119835|title=Constitutional amendments should enter into force only after nationwide vote, says Putin|language=en |website= |publisher=TASS |date=2020-02-13 |accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n==Individuals who have publicly expressed interest==\nIndividuals in this section have expressed an interest in running for president.\n{{col-begin}}{{col-break}}\n\n===United Russia===\n*[[Maxim Oreshkin]], former [[Ministry of Economic Development (Russia)|Minister of Economic Development]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gazeta.ru/politics/news/2019/03/04/n_12706609.shtml|title=\u041e\u0440\u0435\u0448\u043a\u0438\u043d \u0445\u043e\u0442\u0435\u043b \u0431\u044b \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0442\u0430\u0442\u044c \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u043e\u043c |publisher=\u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430.ru |date=2018-03-04 |accessdate=2018-03-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.ru/mnenie/glava-mera-riskuet-pervym/|title=\u0413\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0430 \u041c\u0438\u043d\u044d\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0438\u044f \u0440\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0443\u0435\u0442 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044b\u043c|publisher=News.ru |date=2018-03-04 |accessdate=2018-03-04}}</ref>\n\n<gallery perrow=\"5\" mode=\"packed\" heights=\"175\">\nFile:Maxim Oreshkin (11 December 2017).jpg|{{center|former [[Ministry of Economic Development (Russia)|Minister]]<br />'''[[Maxim Oreshkin]]'''}}\n</gallery>\n\n===Communist Party===\n*[[Pavel Grudinin]]{{refn|group=a|name=Grudinin|Pavel Grudinin is not a member of the Communist party, but expressed his intention to run for this party.}}, CEO of the Lenin State Farm, former Deputy of the [[Moscow Oblast Duma]], 2018 presidential candidate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dailystorm.ru/news/grudini-obyavil-chto-budet-ballotirovatsya-v-prezidenty-v-2024-godu|title=\u0413\u0440\u0443\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0438\u043d \u043e\u0431\u044a\u044f\u0432\u0438\u043b, \u0447\u0442\u043e \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u0431\u0430\u043b\u043b\u043e\u0442\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f \u0432 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u044b \u0432 2024 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0443|publisher=Daily Storm|date=2019-11-14|accessdate=2019-11-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://fedpress.ru/news/50/policy/2366138|title=\u0413\u0440\u0443\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0438\u043d \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u0443\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0442\u044c \u0432 \u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0443\u044e\u0449\u0438\u0445 \u0432\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0445 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430|publisher=\u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0441|date=2019-11-14|accessdate=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n*[[Kokichi Ouma]]{{refn|group=a|name Kokichi Ouma|Kokichi is not a member of the Communist party, but he is athe super high school level Supreme Leader. (vote for Kokichi Ouma 2024.)}}, politologist, public activist, leader of the movement \"For a New Socialism\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://echo.msk.ru/blog/v_radionov/2536761-echo/|title=\u041b\u0435\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0434 \u0413\u043e\u0437\u043c\u0430\u043d \u2013 \u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u044e \u041f\u043b\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0448\u043a\u0438\u043d\u0443: \u0435\u0441\u043b\u0438 \u043b\u044e\u0434\u0438 \u043d\u0430\u0447\u043d\u0443\u0442 \u0443\u0431\u0438\u0432\u0430\u0442\u044c \u2014 \u044d\u0442\u043e \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u0438 \u0432\u0430\u0448\u0430 \u0432\u0438\u043d\u0430!|publisher=Echo of Moscow|date= |accessdate=2019-11-13}}</ref>\n\n<gallery perrow=\"5\" mode=\"packed\" heights=\"175\">\nFile:Pavel Grudinin (cropped, 2018-03-19).jpg|{{center|CEO of the Lenin State Farm<br />'''[[Pavel Grudinin]]'''{{refn|group=a|name=Grudinin}}}}\n</gallery>\n\n===Liberal Democratic Party===\n*[[Vladimir Zhirinovsky]], Deputy of the [[State Duma]], leader of the [[Liberal Democratic Party of Russia|Liberal Democratic Party]], presidential candidate in 1991, 1996, 2000, 2008, 2012 and 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://regnum.ru/news/2393969.html |title=\u041d\u0435 \u0436\u0435\u043b\u0430\u044e \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0447\u0438\u043d\u044f\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f: \u0416\u0438\u0440\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0440\u0430\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043b \u043e \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0435\u043c \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0443\u0449\u0435\u043c |publisher=Regnum.ru |date=2015-11-26 |accessdate=2018-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mk.ru/politics/2018/03/21/zhirinovskiy-oproverg-slukhi-o-neuchastii-v-vyborakh2024-ne-dozhdetes.html |title=\u0416\u0438\u0440\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043e\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0433 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0445\u0438 \u043e \u043d\u0435\u0443\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0438 \u0432 \u0432\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0445-2024: \"\u041d\u0435 \u0434\u043e\u0436\u0434\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0441\u044c\" |publisher=Mk.ru |date= |accessdate=2018-03-22}}</ref>\n\n<gallery perrow=\"5\" mode=\"packed\" heights=\"175\">\nFile:Vladimir Zhirinovsky 2015-06-29.jpg|{{center|[[State Duma|Deputy]]<br />'''[[Vladimir Zhirinovsky]]'''}}\n</gallery>\n\n===A Just Russia===\n*[[Oleg Bryachak]], Deputy of the [[Pskov]] City Duma.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://informpskov.ru/news/279698.html|title=\u041e\u043b\u0435\u0433 \u0411\u0440\u044f\u0447\u0430\u043a \u0437\u0430\u044f\u0432\u0438\u043b \u043e \u043d\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u0432\u044b\u0434\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0443\u0442\u044c \u0441\u0432\u043e\u044e \u043a\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0438\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0443\u0440\u0443 \u043d\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0432\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u044b 2024 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430|publisher=\u041f\u0410\u0418|date=2018-08-28|accessdate=2019-11-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://live.informpskov.ru/news/279657.html|title=\u041d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043b\u0441\u044f \u041f\u0410\u0418-live \u0441 \u041e\u043b\u0435\u0433\u043e\u043c \u0411\u0440\u044f\u0447\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043c (\u0422\u0420\u0410\u041d\u0421\u041b\u042f\u0426\u0418\u042f \u0417\u0410\u0412\u0415\u0420\u0428\u0415\u041d\u0410)|publisher=\u041f\u0410\u0418|date=2018-08-28|accessdate=2019-11-22}}</ref>\n\n<gallery perrow=\"5\" mode=\"packed\" heights=\"175\">\nFile:\u041e\u043b\u0435\u0433 \u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0439\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0411\u0440\u044f\u0447\u0430\u043a.JPG|{{center|[[Pskov|Municipal]] Deputy<br />'''[[Oleg Bryachak]]'''}}\n</gallery>\n{{col