ar=1907|url=https://archive.org/details/foodanddrugsact00greegoog}}\n*[[James Harvey Young]], Pure Food:  Securing the Federal Food and Drugs Act of 1906 (New Jersey:  Princeton University Press, 1989).\n*Mitchell Okun, Fair Play in the Marketplace:  The First Battle for Pure Food and Drugs (Dekalb:  University of Illinois Press, 1986).\n*Suzanne White Junod, Chemistry and Controversy:  Food Additive Regulation, unpublished dissertation, Emory University, 1994.\n*Andrew F. Smith, Pure Ketchup:  A History of America's National Condiment (Columbia:  University of South Carolina Press, 1996)\n*Goodwin, Pure Food, Drug, and Drink Crusaders\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{cite web |url=https://www.visitthecapitol.gov/exhibitions/more-perfect-union-april-2010-september-2011/general-welfare/protecting-nations-food |title=S. 88, Draft bill of the Pure Food and Drug Act |author=59th U.S. Congress |date=December 14, 1905 |work=Chapter 3915, cited 34 U.S. Stats. 768 |publisher=U.S. Capitol Visitor Center |accessdate=April 8, 2013}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://www.fda.gov/regulatoryinformation/legislation/ucm148690.htm |title=THE WILEY ACT |author=59th U.S. Congress |work=Public Law Number 59-384, 34 Stat. 768 |year=1906 |publisher=U.S. Food and Drug Administration |accessdate=April 8, 2013}}\n\n{{Consumer Food Safety|state=collapsed}}\n{{Theodore Roosevelt}}\n\n[[Category:1906 in American politics]]\n[[Category:1906 in law]]\n[[Category:Food and Drug Administration]]\n[[Category:Food law]]\n[[Category:Food safety in the United States]]\n[[Category:History of the United States (1865\u20131918)]]\n[[Category:Presidency of Theodore Roosevelt]]\n[[Category:Progressive Era in the United States]]\n[[Category:United States federal controlled substances legislation]]\n[[Category:United States federal health legislation]]\n", "name_user": "Sal2100", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEnforcement of labeling and future ramifications:avoiding the redirect", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pure_Food_and_Drug_Act"}
{"title_page": "Battle of Dryfe Sands", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict=Battle of Dryfe Sands\n| image=[[File:Johnstone arms.svg|150px]][[File:Arms of Robert Maxwell, Earl of Nithsdale.svg|150px]] \n| caption =Coats of arms of the chief of Clan Johnstone (left) and chief of Clan Maxwell (right)<ref>{{cite book|last1=Crichton-Stuart, Marquess of Bute|first1=John Patrick|last2=Stevenson|first2=John Horne|last3=Lonsdale|first3=H. W.|authorlink1=John Crichton-Stuart, 4th Marquess of Bute|title=The Arms of the Baronial and Police Burghs of Scotland|date=1903|publisher=Blackwood|page=[https://archive.org/details/armsofbaronialpo00buterich/page/418 418]|url=https://archive.org/details/armsofbaronialpo00buterich|accessdate=29 August 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Nicolas|first1=Nicholas Harris|title=The Siege of Carlaverock ... with the Arms of the Earls, Barons, and Knights, who Were Present on the Occasion|date=1828|publisher=Nichols|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cWyt7TTAD7UC&pg=PR25|accessdate=29 August 2017|language=en|page=25}}</ref>\n| partof = Clan Johnstone-Clan Maxwell feud\n| coordinates =\n| date = 6 December 1593<ref name=\"Hewinson\">{{cite book |last=Hewinson |first=James King |year=1912 |title=Dumfriesshire |url=https://archive.org/details/dumfriesshire00hewi |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |page=[https://archive.org/details/dumfriesshire00hewi/page/93 93]}}</ref>\n| place = [[Annandale]], [[Scotland]]\n| result = Clan Johnstone victory\n| combatant1 = [[Clan Johnstone]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Way |first1=George of Plean |last2=Squire |first2=Romilly of Rubislaw |authorlink2=Romilly Squire of Rubislaw |authorlink1=George Way of Plean |year=1994 |title=Collins Scottish Clan & Family Encyclopedia |location=[[Glasgow]] |publisher=[[HarperCollins]] (for the [[Standing Council of Scottish Chiefs]]) |isbn=0-00-470547-5 |pages=178\u2013179}}</ref><br>[[Clan Scott]]<ref name=\"Marchbank\"/><br>[[Clan Graham]]<ref name=\"Marchbank\"/>\n| commander1 = Sir James Johnstone\n| strength1 = 600-800\n| casualties1 =\"heavy\"<br>(only 160 survivors)\n| combatant2 = [[Clan Maxwell]]<ref>Way, George of Plean; Squire, Romily of Rubislaw (1994). pp. 429 - 430.</ref><br>[[Clan Grierson]]<ref>Way, George of Plean; Squire, Romily of Rubislaw. (1994). pp. 152 - 153.</ref><br>[[Clan Pollock]]<ref name=\"Pollock\">Way, George of Plean; Squire, Romily of Rubislaw (1994). pp. 446 - 447.</ref>\n| commander2 = [[John Maxwell, 8th Lord Maxwell]]\n| strength2 = 2,000\n| casualties2 =700 killed\n| notes=\n}}\n\nThe '''Battle of Dryfe Sands''' was a [[Scottish clan]] battle that took place on 6 December 1593, near [[Lockerbie]], [[Scotland]]. It was fought between the  [[Clan Maxwell]] and [[Clan Johnstone]] after several years of feuding between them. The Johnstones won a decisive victory over the Maxwells.\n\n==Background==\n\nIn 1585, [[John Maxwell, 8th Lord Maxwell]], was declared a rebel for having quarreled with the [[Earl of Arran (Scotland)|Earl of Arran]] who was a favorite of [[James VI of Scotland]]. A [[Commission (document)|commission]] was therefore given to Johnstone, Lord of Annandale, who was then the [[Warden of the West Marches]]. Maxwell, having numerous [[vassal]]s and friends, it was thought necessary to send two bands of [[Mercenary|mercenaries]] to support Johnstone. However, these two companies, that were commanded by captains Cranston and Lammie, were attacked at Crawfordmoor and cut to pieces by a party of Maxwells who were under the command of Robert Maxwell, natural brother to the chief. He followed up this advantage by burning Johnstone's [[Lochwood Tower|Lochwood Castle]]. In a subsequent conflict Johnstone himself was defeated and taken prisoner, and is said to have died of the grief at the disgrace which he had sustained.<ref name=\"M'Vitie\">{{cite book |last=M'Vitie |first=William |year=1858 |title=The Battle of Dryfe Sands |url=https://archive.org/details/battleofdryfesan00mvit |location=[[Lockerbie]] |publisher=Printed by D. Halliday |pages=[https://archive.org/details/battleofdryfesan00mvit/page/n12 1]\u20137}}</ref>\n\nMaxwell was soon restored in the King's favor, and obtained the Wardenship of the West Marches. He subscribed a bond of alliance with Lord James Johnstone, son of the slain Lord Johnstone, and for some time the two clans lived in peace. However, the feud was revived in 1593 when Johnstone of Wamphray who was a relation of Lord Johnstone, along with some friends, went to [[Nithsdale]] and took away a horse which belonged to Crichton of [[Sanquhar Castle|Sanquhar]]. They were pursued by Crichton and some of his friends who took Johnstone prisoner and hanged him from a tree. A nephew of Johnstone of Wamphrey, William Johnstone, managed to escape from the Crichtons and raised a powerful band of Johnstones, again going over to Nithsdale, and swept the country of cattle. Crichton of Sanquhar and Douglas of Drumlanrig raising what forces they could muster attacked the Johnstones at a place called Biddes-burn, but were completely defeated and the Johnstones carried off the spoil.<ref name=\"M'Vitie\"/> In this encounter several Johnstones and fifteen Crichtons were killed.<ref name=\"Graham\">{{cite book |last=Graham |first=F.R |year=1909 |title=History of the Johnstones, 1191-1909, with descriptions of border life |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofjohnsto00grah |location=[[Edinburgh]] |publisher=[[W. & A.K. Johnston & G.W. Bacon Ltd.]] |pages=[https://archive.org/details/historyofjohnsto00grah/page/82 82]\u201385}}</ref>\n\nThe men of Nithsdale resolved that they would apply to Lord Maxwell for assistance and protection. However, Maxwell would not easily embrace their cause because of his recent reconciliation with Johnstone. They overcame this by entering into a bond of [[manrent]] with Maxwell and therefore became his followers and [[Homage (feudal)|liege-men]]. In return he granted to them a bond of maintenance or protection in which he bound himself to maintain them in their feuds. Some of the most powerful families in Dumfriesshire therefore became vassals of the house of Maxwell, including: [[Clan Kirkpatrick|Kirkpatrick of Closeburn]], Douglas of Drumlanrig (ancestor of the [[Duke of Queensberry]]), [[Clan Crichton|Crichton of Sanquhar]] (ancestor of the [[Earl of Dumfries]]), Stuart of [[Castlemilk]], Stuart of Garlies (ancestor of the [[Earl of Galloway]]), the Murrays, Lord Annandale, [[Clan Grierson|Grierson of Lag]], Gordon of Lochmaben, and many others in the south-west of Scotland, all binding themselves as vassals of Maxwell.<ref name=\"M'Vitie\"/>\n\nJohnstone was subsequently informed that Crichton, Douglas and a number of others had put themselves under the protection of Maxwell and the warfare between the rival clans was instantly renewed. [[Duke of Buccleuch#Feudal barons of Buccleuch (1488)|Buccleuch]], chief of the Scotts, who was a near relation of Johnstone, came to his assistance with his clan, which not only included the [[Clan Scott]] but also the [[Clan Eliott]], [[Clan Armstrong]] and [[Clan Graham]]. Johnstone having been reinforced, he surprised and cut to pieces a party of Maxwells who were stationed at [[Lochmaben]]. Among the slain was Robert Maxwell, brother of the chief, who had burnt Johnstone's castle at Lochwood. The Maxwells had taken refuge in Lochmaben Church, which they defended for some time, until the Johnstones burnt the church and everyone inside it.<ref name=\"M'Vitie\"/>\n \n==Battle==\n[[File:CaerlaverockCastle01.jpg|thumb|Ruins of [[Caerlaverock Castle]], historic seat of the chiefs of Clan Maxwell]]\nLord Maxwell, highly incensed by this outrage, entered into [[Annandale]] with 2,000 men, including all of the barons of Nithsdale and also some Royal troops.<ref name=\"M'Vitie\"/> He apparently offered a reward of a \u00a310 land to anyone who could bring him Johnstone's head or hand.<ref name=\"Graham\"/> The Scotts were a fierce and war-like clan and Dame Margaret Johnstone, being a daughter of Buccleuch, three hundred Scotts came to join Johnstone of Lochwood. As Buccleuch was away, they were led by the [[Gideon Murray|Laird of Elibank]]. They were joined by two of Johnstone's retainers near Lockerbie, Johnstone of Kirktoun, who had a large following and Johnstone of Lockerbie, who had fifty men. They were also joined by the Grahams from the [[Debatable Lands]], who were apparently always ready to fight the Maxwells. Johnstone took the high ground above where the [[Dryfe Water|Dryfe]] joines the [[River Annan|Annan]]. Upon Maxwell's approach a small body of the Johnstones came forward from the rest and taunted the Maxwells who were then tempted up the slope. The Johnstones, Scotts and Grahams then left the heights and rushed down on their enemies.<ref name=\"Marchbank\">{{cite book |last=Marchbank |first=Angus |year=1901 |title=Upper Annandale; its history and traditions |url=https://archive.org/details/upperannandaleit00marciala |location=[[Paisley, Renfrewshire]] |publisher=Parlane |pages=[https://archive.org/details/upperannandaleit00marciala/page/76 76]\u201377}}</ref> A desperate conflict took place in which Johnstone gained the victory. Lord Maxwell apparently performed \"prodigies\" of valor but was among the slain. Many of his followers were also slain. The barons of Lag, Closeburn and Drumlanrig escaped thanks to their horses.<ref name=\"M'Vitie\"/>\n\nAccording to Marchbank, 700 Maxwells were killed in the battle.<ref name=\"Marchbank\"/> John Pollock, son of the chief of [[Clan Pollock]], was killed supporting the Maxwells.<ref name=\"Pollock\"/>  Some who escaped are said to have had \"Lockerbie licks\" on their faces, caused by being slashed by the swords of pursuing horsemen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dryfesdalelodge.org.uk/resources/thebattleofdryfesands.pdf|title=Battle of Dryfe Sands|accessdate=8 June 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150623154146/http://www.dryfesdalelodge.org.uk/resources/thebattleofdryfesands.pdf|archivedate=23 June 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> However, it is likely that Johnstone's losses were also heavy as in 1594 he obtained a [[respite (law)|respite]] from the King for himself and just eight [[20 (number)|score]] (160) surviving followers.<ref name=\"Graham\"/> Among those killed on Johnstone's side was Bell of Albie who was killed whilst in pursuit of the Maxwells.<ref>{{cite book |last=Lewis |first=Samuel |year=1989 |title=A Topographical Dictionary of Scotland: Comprising the Several Counties, Islands, Cities, Burgh and Market Towns, Parishes, and Principal Villages with Historical and Statistical Descriptions |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WaHrCqQIjt8C&pg=PA59&lpg=PA59&dq=Bell+of+Albie+Dryfe+Sands&source=bl&ots=u8Sk_1cHmJ&sig=ACfU3U1ysm_JtQe9LevleywGXsO2lXPI1A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiglKW7-OnmAhU9SRUIHVM2CPQQ6AEwBHoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=Bell%20of%20Albie%20Dryfe%20Sands&f=false |publisher=Genealogical Publishing Company |page=59}}</ref> According to the ''[[Statistical Accounts of Scotland|New Statistical Account of Scotland]]'', \"the Albie Thorn\" was planted on the spot where Bell of Albie fell, which was within 500 yards of the church.<ref>{{cite book |year=1834 |title=The New Statistical Account of Scotland |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Msg9AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA183&lpg=PA183&dq=Bell+of+Albie+Dryfe+Sands&source=bl&ots=-Tn6qQJJ5e&sig=ACfU3U03A8KE-XvOz13Fp51fIlR4PlzoFg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiglKW7-OnmAhU9SRUIHVM2CPQQ6AEwBXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=Bell%20of%20Albie%20Dryfe%20Sands&f=false |volume=Volume 2 |publisher=[[Blackwood (publishing house)|Blackwood]] |page=183}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\n\nLord Maxwell's cousin, William Maxwell, 5th [[Lord Herries of Terregles]], became the next Warden of the West Marches. He ignored the respite and tried to capture Johnstone's followers. In doing so he kept the country in a state of confusion and as a result the King superseded him as the Warden with Johnstone himself.<ref name=\"Graham\"/> Douglas of Drumlanrig could not forgive the defeat at Dryfe Sands, and on 13 July 1597 attacked Johnstone with his \"assisters\" but failed to capture two rebel Armstrongs. As a result of this fight, Johnstone was deprived of the Wardenship, but it was given to his ally, [[Sir John Carmichael]].<ref name=\"Graham\"/> In 1608, Sir James Johnstone, now the Warden of the Marches, met up with [[John Maxwell, 9th Lord Maxwell]] who was son of the slain Warden, at [[Tinwald, Dumfries and Galloway|Tinwald]] for the purpose of ending the feud peaceably. However, Maxwell shot Johnstone and then fled to the [[Continental Europe|Continent]]. When he returned he was executed in [[Edinburgh]], in 1613, for [[High treason in the United Kingdom|high treason]] and for the slaying of the Warden of the Marches.<ref name=\"Hewinson\"/>\n\nBetween 1591 and 1594 the peace in Scotland had been disturbed on several occasions caused by the activities of [[Francis Stewart, 5th Earl of Bothwell]] who was a nephew of the third husband of [[Mary, Queen of Scots]], [[James Hepburn, 4th Earl of Bothwell]]. This had resulted in a serious revolt of the Catholic dissidents in the north-east. However, with the death of Lord Maxwell, who was a staunch Catholic, at the Battle of Dryfe Sands in 1593 and the fall of the northern Earls after the [[Battle of Glenlivet]] in 1594, the Catholic cause was destroyed.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mackay |first=Dr James |authorlink=James A. Mackay |year=1999 |title=Scottish History |location=[[Bath, Somerset]] |publisher=[[Parragon]] |page=194 |isbn=0752530380}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Canmore |num=66889|desc=Dryfesands}}\n*{{Canmore |num=66847|desc=Albie Thorn}}\n*[https://sites.google.com/site/mainlymilitarybooks/dryfe-sand-1593 Military books - Dryfe Sand 1593]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110515200554/http://www.dryfesdalelodge.org.uk/resources/thebattleofdryfesands.pdf Battle of Dryfe Sands]\n\n{{Scottish clan battles}}\n\n[[Category:1596 in Scotland]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish clan battles|Dryfe Sands]]\n[[Category:Clan Maxwell]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict=Battle of Dryfe Sands\n| image=[[File:Johnstone arms.svg|150px]][[File:Arms of Robert Maxwell, Earl of Nithsdale.svg|150px]] \n| caption =Coats of arms of the chief of Clan Johnstone (left) and chief of Clan Maxwell (right)<ref>{{cite book|last1=Crichton-Stuart, Marquess of Bute|first1=John Patrick|last2=Stevenson|first2=John Horne|last3=Lonsdale|first3=H. W.|authorlink1=John Crichton-Stuart, 4th Marquess of Bute|title=The Arms of the Baronial and Police Burghs of Scotland|date=1903|publisher=Blackwood|page=[https://archive.org/details/armsofbaronialpo00buterich/page/418 418]|url=https://archive.org/details/armsofbaronialpo00buterich|accessdate=29 August 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Nicolas|first1=Nicholas Harris|title=The Siege of Carlaverock ... with the Arms of the Earls, Barons, and Knights, who Were Present on the Occasion|date=1828|publisher=Nichols|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cWyt7TTAD7UC&pg=PR25|accessdate=29 August 2017|language=en|page=25}}</ref>\n| partof = Clan Johnstone-Clan Maxwell feud\n| coordinates =\n| date = 6 December 1593<ref name=\"Hewinson\">{{cite book |last=Hewinson |first=James King |year=1912 |title=Dumfriesshire |url=https://archive.org/details/dumfriesshire00hewi |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |page=[https://archive.org/details/dumfriesshire00hewi/page/93 93]}}</ref>\n| place = [[Annandale]], [[Scotland]]\n| result = Clan Johnstone victory\n| combatant1 = [[Clan Johnstone]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Way |first1=George of Plean |last2=Squire |first2=Romilly of Rubislaw |authorlink2=Romilly Squire of Rubislaw |authorlink1=George Way of Plean |year=1994 |title=Collins Scottish Clan & Family Encyclopedia |location=[[Glasgow]] |publisher=[[HarperCollins]] (for the [[Standing Council of Scottish Chiefs]]) |isbn=0-00-470547-5 |pages=178\u2013179}}</ref><br>[[Clan Scott]]<ref name=\"Marchbank\"/><br>[[Clan Graham]]<ref name=\"Marchbank\"/>\n| commander1 = Sir James Johnstone\n| strength1 = 600-800\n| casualties1 =\"heavy\"<br>(only 160 survivors)\n| combatant2 = [[Clan Maxwell]]<ref>Way, George of Plean; Squire, Romily of Rubislaw (1994). pp. 429 - 430.</ref><br>[[Clan Grierson]]<ref>Way, George of Plean; Squire, Romily of Rubislaw. (1994). pp. 152 - 153.</ref><br>[[Clan Pollock]]<ref name=\"Pollock\">Way, George of Plean; Squire, Romily of Rubislaw (1994). pp. 446 - 447.</ref>\n| commander2 = [[John Maxwell, 8th Lord Maxwell]]\n| strength2 = 2,000\n| casualties2 =700 killed\n| notes=\n}}\n\nThe '''Battle of Dryfe Sands''' was a [[Scottish clan]] battle that took place on 6 December 1593, near [[Lockerbie]], [[Scotland]]. It was fought between the  [[Clan Maxwell]] and [[Clan Johnstone]] after several years of feuding between them. The Johnstones won a decisive victory over the Maxwells.\n\n==Background==\n\nIn 1585, [[John Maxwell, 8th Lord Maxwell]], was declared a rebel for having quarreled with the [[Earl of Arran (Scotland)|Earl of Arran]] who was a favorite of [[James VI of Scotland]]. A [[Commission (document)|commission]] was therefore given to Johnstone, Lord of Annandale, who was then the [[Warden of the West Marches]]. Maxwell, having numerous [[vassal]]s and friends, it was thought necessary to send two bands of [[Mercenary|mercenaries]] to support Johnstone. However, these two companies, that were commanded by captains Cranston and Lammie, were attacked at Crawfordmoor and cut to pieces by a party of Maxwells who were under the command of Robert Maxwell, natural brother to the chief. He followed up this advantage by burning Johnstone's [[Lochwood Tower|Lochwood Castle]]. In a subsequent conflict Johnstone himself was defeated and taken prisoner, and is said to have died of the grief at the disgrace which he had sustained.<ref name=\"M'Vitie\">{{cite book |last=M'Vitie |first=William |year=1858 |title=The Battle of Dryfe Sands |url=https://archive.org/details/battleofdryfesan00mvit |location=[[Lockerbie]] |publisher=Printed by D. Halliday |pages=[https://archive.org/details/battleofdryfesan00mvit/page/n12 1]\u20137}}</ref>\n\nMaxwell was soon restored in the King's favor, and obtained the Wardenship of the West Marches. He subscribed a bond of alliance with Lord James Johnstone, son of the slain Lord Johnstone, and for some time the two clans lived in peace. However, the feud was revived in 1593 when Johnstone of Wamphray who was a relation of Lord Johnstone, along with some friends, went to [[Nithsdale]] and took away a horse which belonged to Crichton of [[Sanquhar Castle|Sanquhar]]. They were pursued by Crichton and some of his friends who took Johnstone prisoner and hanged him from a tree. A nephew of Johnstone of Wamphrey, William Johnstone, managed to escape from the Crichtons and raised a powerful band of Johnstones, again going over to Nithsdale, and swept the country of cattle. Crichton of Sanquhar and Douglas of Drumlanrig raising what forces they could muster attacked the Johnstones at a place called Biddes-burn, but were completely defeated and the Johnstones carried off the spoil.<ref name=\"M'Vitie\"/> In this encounter several Johnstones and fifteen Crichtons were killed.<ref name=\"Graham\">{{cite book |last=Graham |first=F.R |year=1909 |title=History of the Johnstones, 1191-1909, with descriptions of border life |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofjohnsto00grah |location=[[Edinburgh]] |publisher=[[W. & A.K. Johnston & G.W. Bacon Ltd.]] |pages=[https://archive.org/details/historyofjohnsto00grah/page/82 82]\u201385}}</ref>\n\nThe men of Nithsdale resolved that they would apply to Lord Maxwell for assistance and protection. However, Maxwell would not easily embrace their cause because of his recent reconciliation with Johnstone. They overcame this by entering into a bond of [[manrent]] with Maxwell and therefore became his followers and [[Homage (feudal)|liege-men]]. In return he granted to them a bond of maintenance or protection in which he bound himself to maintain them in their feuds. Some of the most powerful families in Dumfriesshire therefore became vassals of the house of Maxwell, including: [[Clan Kirkpatrick|Kirkpatrick of Closeburn]], Douglas of Drumlanrig (ancestor of the [[Duke of Queensberry]]), [[Clan Crichton|Crichton of Sanquhar]] (ancestor of the [[Earl of Dumfries]]), Stuart of [[Castlemilk]], Stuart of Garlies (ancestor of the [[Earl of Galloway]]), the Murrays, Lord Annandale, [[Clan Grierson|Grierson of Lag]], Gordon of Lochmaben, and many others in the south-west of Scotland, all binding themselves as vassals of Maxwell.<ref name=\"M'Vitie\"/>\n\nJohnstone was subsequently informed that Crichton, Douglas and a number of others had put themselves under the protection of Maxwell and the warfare between the rival clans was instantly renewed. [[Duke of Buccleuch#Feudal barons of Buccleuch (1488)|Buccleuch]], chief of the Scotts, who was a near relation of Johnstone, came to his assistance with his clan, which not only included the [[Clan Scott]] but also the [[Clan Eliott]], [[Clan Armstrong]] and [[Clan Graham]]. Johnstone having been reinforced, he surprised and cut to pieces a party of Maxwells who were stationed at [[Lochmaben]]. Among the slain was Robert Maxwell, brother of the chief, who had burnt Johnstone's castle at Lochwood. The Maxwells had taken refuge in Lochmaben Church, which they defended for some time, until the Johnstones burnt the church and everyone inside it.<ref name=\"M'Vitie\"/>\n \n==Battle==\n[[File:CaerlaverockCastle01.jpg|thumb|Ruins of [[Caerlaverock Castle]], historic seat of the chiefs of Clan Maxwell]]\nLord Maxwell, highly incensed by this outrage, entered into [[Annandale]] with 2,000 men, including all of the barons of Nithsdale and also some Royal troops.<ref name=\"M'Vitie\"/> He apparently offered a reward of a \u00a310 land to anyone who could bring him Johnstone's head or hand.<ref name=\"Graham\"/> The Scotts were a fierce and war-like clan and Dame Margaret Johnstone, being a daughter of Buccleuch, three hundred Scotts came to join Johnstone of Lochwood. As Buccleuch was away, they were led by the [[Lord Elibank|Laird of Elibank]]. They were joined by two of Johnstone's retainers near Lockerbie, Johnstone of Kirktoun, who had a large following and Johnstone of Lockerbie, who had fifty men. They were also joined by the Grahams from the [[Debatable Lands]], who were apparently always ready to fight the Maxwells. Johnstone took the high ground above where the [[Dryfe Water|Dryfe]] joines the [[River Annan|Annan]]. Upon Maxwell's approach a small body of the Johnstones came forward from the rest and taunted the Maxwells who were then tempted up the slope. The Johnstones, Scotts and Grahams then left the heights and rushed down on their enemies.<ref name=\"Marchbank\">{{cite book |last=Marchbank |first=Angus |year=1901 |title=Upper Annandale; its history and traditions |url=https://archive.org/details/upperannandaleit00marciala |location=[[Paisley, Renfrewshire]] |publisher=Parlane |pages=[https://archive.org/details/upperannandaleit00marciala/page/76 76]\u201377}}</ref> A desperate conflict took place in which Johnstone gained the victory. Lord Maxwell apparently performed \"prodigies\" of valor but was among the slain. Many of his followers were also slain. The barons of Lag, Closeburn and Drumlanrig escaped thanks to their horses.<ref name=\"M'Vitie\"/>\n\nAccording to Marchbank, 700 Maxwells were killed in the battle.<ref name=\"Marchbank\"/> John Pollock, son of the chief of [[Clan Pollock]], was killed supporting the Maxwells.<ref name=\"Pollock\"/>  Some who escaped are said to have had \"Lockerbie licks\" on their faces, caused by being slashed by the swords of pursuing horsemen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dryfesdalelodge.org.uk/resources/thebattleofdryfesands.pdf|title=Battle of Dryfe Sands|accessdate=8 June 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150623154146/http://www.dryfesdalelodge.org.uk/resources/thebattleofdryfesands.pdf|archivedate=23 June 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> However, it is likely that Johnstone's losses were also heavy as in 1594 he obtained a [[respite (law)|respite]] from the King for himself and just eight [[20 (number)|score]] (160) surviving followers.<ref name=\"Graham\"/> Among those killed on Johnstone's side was Bell of Albie who was killed whilst in pursuit of the Maxwells.<ref>{{cite book |last=Lewis |first=Samuel |year=1989 |title=A Topographical Dictionary of Scotland: Comprising the Several Counties, Islands, Cities, Burgh and Market Towns, Parishes, and Principal Villages with Historical and Statistical Descriptions |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WaHrCqQIjt8C&pg=PA59&lpg=PA59&dq=Bell+of+Albie+Dryfe+Sands&source=bl&ots=u8Sk_1cHmJ&sig=ACfU3U1ysm_JtQe9LevleywGXsO2lXPI1A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiglKW7-OnmAhU9SRUIHVM2CPQQ6AEwBHoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=Bell%20of%20Albie%20Dryfe%20Sands&f=false |publisher=Genealogical Publishing Company |page=59}}</ref> According to the ''[[Statistical Accounts of Scotland|New Statistical Account of Scotland]]'', \"the Albie Thorn\" was planted on the spot where Bell of Albie fell, which was within 500 yards of the church.<ref>{{cite book |year=1834 |title=The New Statistical Account of Scotland |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Msg9AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA183&lpg=PA183&dq=Bell+of+Albie+Dryfe+Sands&source=bl&ots=-Tn6qQJJ5e&sig=ACfU3U03A8KE-XvOz13Fp51fIlR4PlzoFg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiglKW7-OnmAhU9SRUIHVM2CPQQ6AEwBXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=Bell%20of%20Albie%20Dryfe%20Sands&f=false |volume=Volume 2 |publisher=[[Blackwood (publishing house)|Blackwood]] |page=183}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\n\nLord Maxwell's cousin, William Maxwell, 5th [[Lord Herries of Terregles]], became the next Warden of the West Marches. He ignored the respite and tried to capture Johnstone's followers. In doing so he kept the country in a state of confusion and as a result the King superseded him as the Warden with Johnstone himself.<ref name=\"Graham\"/> Douglas of Drumlanrig could not forgive the defeat at Dryfe Sands, and on 13 July 1597 attacked Johnstone with his \"assisters\" but failed to capture two rebel Armstrongs. As a result of this fight, Johnstone was deprived of the Wardenship, but it was given to his ally, [[Sir John Carmichael]].<ref name=\"Graham\"/> In 1608, Sir James Johnstone, now the Warden of the Marches, met up with [[John Maxwell, 9th Lord Maxwell]] who was son of the slain Warden, at [[Tinwald, Dumfries and Galloway|Tinwald]] for the purpose of ending the feud peaceably. However, Maxwell shot Johnstone and then fled to the [[Continental Europe|Continent]]. When he returned he was executed in [[Edinburgh]], in 1613, for [[High treason in the United Kingdom|high treason]] and for the slaying of the Warden of the Marches.<ref name=\"Hewinson\"/>\n\nBetween 1591 and 1594 the peace in Scotland had been disturbed on several occasions caused by the activities of [[Francis Stewart, 5th Earl of Bothwell]] who was a nephew of the third husband of [[Mary, Queen of Scots]], [[James Hepburn, 4th Earl of Bothwell]]. This had resulted in a serious revolt of the Catholic dissidents in the north-east. However, with the death of Lord Maxwell, who was a staunch Catholic, at the Battle of Dryfe Sands in 1593 and the fall of the northern Earls after the [[Battle of Glenlivet]] in 1594, the Catholic cause was destroyed.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mackay |first=Dr James |authorlink=James A. Mackay |year=1999 |title=Scottish History |location=[[Bath, Somerset]] |publisher=[[Parragon]] |page=194 |isbn=0752530380}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Canmore |num=66889|desc=Dryfesands}}\n*{{Canmore |num=66847|desc=Albie Thorn}}\n*[https://sites.google.com/site/mainlymilitarybooks/dryfe-sand-1593 Military books - Dryfe Sand 1593]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110515200554/http://www.dryfesdalelodge.org.uk/resources/thebattleofdryfesands.pdf Battle of Dryfe Sands]\n\n{{Scottish clan battles}}\n\n[[Category:1596 in Scotland]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish clan battles|Dryfe Sands]]\n[[Category:Clan Maxwell]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBattle:link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Dryfe_Sands"}
